// Unit 20: Die Versicherung
// Level: B1

const UNIT_20 =
{n:20,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Die Versicherung",sub:"Health insurance maze, compound nouns, relative clauses with prepositions, adverbial conjunctions",icon:"🏥",level:"B1.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 1: "Der Papierstapel" — Story intro (18 words, 24 steps)
// Scene 1: Kitchen table of despair
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l1",title:"Der Papierstapel",icon:"📄",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Papierstapel",desc:"Verumius sitzt an seinem K\u00fcchentisch. Vor ihm liegen zwanzig Briefe von der Krankenkasse. Er versteht kein Wort.",goals:["Lerne Vokabeln rund um Gesundheit und Versicherung","Erlebe Verumius im Kampf mit deutscher B\u00fcrokratie","Verstehe, warum Krankenversicherung in Deutschland wichtig ist"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"comedy",art:"de-ber-kitchen-papers",trg:"Verumius sitzt an seinem K\u00fcchentisch. Vor ihm liegen zwanzig Briefe, f\u00fcnf Brosch\u00fcren und drei Formulare. Alle kommen von der Krankenkasse. Er versteht kein Wort.",src:"Verumius sits at his kitchen table. In front of him lie twenty letters, five brochures, and three forms. They all come from the health insurance company. He does not understand a single word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Versicherung",src:"the insurance",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From versichern (to insure/assure).\nVer- + sicher (safe) + -ung = making safe.",example:"A: Hast du eine Krankenversicherung?\nB: Ja, ich bin bei der TK versichert.\nA: Ist das eine gute Versicherung?\nB: Ja, die Leistungen sind sehr gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have health insurance?\nB: Yes, I am insured with TK.\nA: Is that a good insurance?\nB: Yes, the benefits are very good.",funFact:"Germans are famously over-insured: liability, legal protection, glass breakage, even dog insurance exists. The word itself means 'making something safe.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Krankenwagen",src:"the ambulance",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Krank (sick) + Wagen (vehicle).\nLiterally: the sick-car. Call 112 in emergencies.",example:"A: Ruft den Krankenwagen!\nB: Was ist passiert?\nA: Der Mann ist gest\u00fcrzt.\nB: Ich rufe sofort die 112 an.",exampleSrc:"A: Call the ambulance!\nB: What happened?\nA: The man fell down.\nB: I will call 112 right away.",funFact:"Unlike the US, the Krankenwagen ride is covered by your Versicherung. In emergencies, call 112. This number works across all of Europe."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kosten",src:"the costs, the expenses",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Always plural in this meaning.\n'Die Kosten steigen' is Germany's favorite headline.",example:"A: Wie hoch sind die Kosten?\nB: Die Kosten betragen 200 Euro pro Monat.\nA: Das ist teuer!\nB: Ja, aber die Versicherung deckt viel ab.",exampleSrc:"A: How high are the costs?\nB: The costs amount to 200 euros per month.\nA: That is expensive!\nB: Yes, but the insurance covers a lot.",funFact:"From Latin 'constare' (to stand firm at a price). No singular form when it means expenses. 'Die Kosten steigen' (costs are rising) appears in German news almost daily."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Patient",src:"the patient (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Weak masculine noun (N-Deklination).\nDen Patienten, dem Patienten in all other cases.",example:"A: Der Patient wartet seit einer Stunde.\nB: Welcher Patient?\nA: Der Patient mit den Kopfschmerzen.\nB: Ah, ich rufe ihn gleich auf.",exampleSrc:"A: The patient has been waiting for an hour.\nB: Which patient?\nA: The patient with the headache.\nB: Ah, I will call him in shortly.",funFact:"From Latin 'patiens' (suffering/enduring). The patient literally endures. Same root as 'patience.' A weak masculine noun: der Patient but den/dem Patienten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Patientin",src:"the patient (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine form of Patient.\nThe -in suffix creates feminine person nouns.",example:"A: Wie geht es der Patientin?\nB: Die Patientin f\u00fchlt sich besser.\nA: Kann sie morgen nach Hause?\nB: Ja, wenn die Untersuchung gut ausf\u00e4llt.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the patient doing?\nB: The patient is feeling better.\nA: Can she go home tomorrow?\nB: Yes, if the examination goes well.",funFact:"The -in suffix creates feminine versions of person nouns. Der Patient becomes die Patientin. German insists on gendered forms for people, though modern usage is evolving."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Untersuchung",src:"the examination, the checkup",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Unter (under) + such (seek) + -ung.\nMedical exam, investigation, or scientific study.",example:"A: Wann ist Ihre n\u00e4chste Untersuchung?\nB: N\u00e4chste Woche beim Hausarzt.\nA: Ist es eine Routineuntersuchung?\nB: Ja, ich gehe einmal im Jahr.",exampleSrc:"A: When is your next checkup?\nB: Next week at the family doctor.\nA: Is it a routine checkup?\nB: Yes, I go once a year.",funFact:"One word covers medical checkups, police investigations, and scientific studies. 'Zur Untersuchung gehen' means going for a medical exam. A seeking-under."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Therapie",src:"the therapy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Greek 'therapeia' (healing).\nAll covered by Krankenkasse if prescribed by a doctor.",example:"A: Brauche ich eine Therapie?\nB: Ja, ich empfehle Physiotherapie.\nA: Wie oft pro Woche?\nB: Zweimal. Die Krankenkasse zahlt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do I need therapy?\nB: Yes, I recommend physiotherapy.\nA: How often per week?\nB: Twice. The health insurance pays.",funFact:"Germans love therapy: Physiotherapie, Psychotherapie, Ergotherapie. All covered by the Krankenkasse if your doctor prescribes them. The German system is thorough."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Operation",src:"the operation, the surgery",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin. Abbreviated as 'OP' in hospitals.\nOP-Saal = operating room.",example:"A: War die Operation erfolgreich?\nB: Ja, alles ist gut gelaufen.\nA: Wie lange dauert die Erholung?\nB: Etwa zwei Wochen, sagt der Arzt.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the operation successful?\nB: Yes, everything went well.\nA: How long does the recovery take?\nB: About two weeks, says the doctor.",funFact:"Same word, borrowed from Latin. Abbreviated as 'OP' in German hospitals. 'Operiert werden' (to be operated on) uses passive voice. The OP-Saal (operating room) is where it happens."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Klinik",src:"the clinic, the hospital",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Greek 'kline' (bed).\nLarger than a Praxis, smaller than a Universit\u00e4tsklinikum.",example:"A: In welcher Klinik waren Sie?\nB: In der Charit\u00e9. Die ist sehr bekannt.\nA: Waren die \u00c4rzte gut?\nB: Ausgezeichnet. Ich kann die Klinik empfehlen.",exampleSrc:"A: Which clinic were you at?\nB: At the Charit\u00e9. It is very well known.\nA: Were the doctors good?\nB: Excellent. I can recommend the clinic.",funFact:"A Klinik is a hospital or specialized medical center. Larger than a Praxis (doctor's office), smaller than a Universit\u00e4tsklinikum. Germans distinguish these carefully."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Medizin",src:"the medicine, the field of medicine",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Both the substance and the academic field.\n'Medizin studieren' AND 'Medizin nehmen.'",example:"A: Studierst du Medizin?\nB: Nein, ich nehme nur Medizin gegen Husten.\nA: Ach so! Das sind zwei verschiedene Bedeutungen.\nB: Genau. Kontext ist alles.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you study medicine?\nB: No, I only take medicine for a cough.\nA: Oh! Those are two different meanings.\nB: Exactly. Context is everything.",funFact:"One word, two meanings. 'Medizin studieren' (to study medicine) and 'Medizin nehmen' (to take medicine). From Latin 'medicina.' Context decides."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erk\u00e4ltung",src:"the cold (illness)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'kalt' (cold). Literally: a colding.\nThe most common reason Germans visit the Arzt.",example:"A: Ich habe eine schlimme Erk\u00e4ltung.\nB: Seit wann?\nA: Seit drei Tagen. Husten und Schnupfen.\nB: Bleib im Bett und trink viel Tee.",exampleSrc:"A: I have a bad cold.\nB: Since when?\nA: For three days. Cough and runny nose.\nB: Stay in bed and drink lots of tea.",funFact:"Germans believe cold weather causes colds. 'Sich erk\u00e4lten' (to catch a cold). This is the most common reason Germans visit the Arzt."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"bewildered",art:"de-ber-kitchen-papers",trg:"Verumius liest laut vor: 'Krankenversicherungsbeitragsbemessungsgrenze.' Ein Wort. Sechsundvierzig Buchstaben. Er z\u00e4hlt zweimal. Mia schreibt von nebenan: 'Das ist normal. Willkommen in Deutschland.'",src:"Verumius reads aloud: 'Health insurance contribution assessment ceiling.' One word. Forty-six letters. He counts twice. Mia texts from next door: 'That is normal. Welcome to Germany.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verletzung",src:"the injury",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From verletzen (to injure).\nVer- + letzen (to damage). 'Schwere Verletzung' = serious injury.",example:"A: Was f\u00fcr eine Verletzung haben Sie?\nB: Ich habe eine Verletzung am Knie.\nA: Wie ist das passiert?\nB: Ich bin beim Joggen gest\u00fcrzt.",exampleSrc:"A: What kind of injury do you have?\nB: I have a knee injury.\nA: How did that happen?\nB: I fell while jogging.",funFact:"The Unfallversicherung (accident insurance) covers Verletzungen at work. From 'verletzen' (to injure): ver- intensifies, letzen means to damage."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Notfall",src:"the emergency",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Not (need/emergency) + Fall (case).\n'Im Notfall' = in an emergency. Leads to Notaufnahme, Notruf.",example:"A: Ist das ein Notfall?\nB: Ja, rufen Sie sofort die 112 an!\nA: Was soll ich sagen?\nB: Sagen Sie, wo Sie sind und was passiert ist.",exampleSrc:"A: Is this an emergency?\nB: Yes, call 112 immediately!\nA: What should I say?\nB: Say where you are and what happened.",funFact:"The most important compound for survival in Germany. One tiny word 'Not' spawns Notfall, Notaufnahme, Notarzt, Notruf, Notausgang. Learn Not, unlock five words."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Notaufnahme",src:"the emergency room",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Not (emergency) + Aufnahme (intake/admission).\nOpen 24/7. Bring your Versichertenkarte.",example:"A: Wo ist die Notaufnahme?\nB: Im Erdgeschoss, links um die Ecke.\nA: Muss ich lange warten?\nB: Das h\u00e4ngt davon ab, wie voll es ist.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the emergency room?\nB: On the ground floor, left around the corner.\nA: Do I have to wait long?\nB: That depends on how busy it is.",funFact:"The emergency room. Where you go when it is a Notfall. Open 24/7. Bring your Versichertenkarte. Without it, you still get treated but the paperwork gets complicated."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Notruf",src:"the emergency call",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Not (emergency) + Ruf (call).\n112 in all of Europe, free from any phone.",example:"A: Kennst du den Notruf?\nB: Ja, 112 f\u00fcr Krankenwagen und Feuerwehr.\nA: Und die Polizei?\nB: Die Polizei hat die 110.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know the emergency number?\nB: Yes, 112 for ambulance and fire department.\nA: And the police?\nB: The police have 110.",funFact:"112 works in all of Europe. Free from any phone, even without a SIM card. 'Den Notruf w\u00e4hlen' (to dial the emergency number). The most important number to memorize in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"versichern",src:"to insure, to assure",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + sicher (safe/sure).\nReflexive for insurance, transitive for assurance.",example:"A: Bist du krankenversichert?\nB: Ja, ich habe mich bei der TK versichert.\nA: Ich versichere dir, das ist eine gute Wahl.\nB: Danke f\u00fcr den Tipp!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have health insurance?\nB: Yes, I insured myself with TK.\nA: I assure you, that is a good choice.\nB: Thanks for the tip!",funFact:"'Sich versichern' (to get insured). 'Ich versichere Ihnen...' (I assure you...). Reflexive for insurance, transitive for assurance. One verb, two very different uses."},
{type:"teach",trg:"behandeln",src:"to treat (medically), to handle",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + handeln (to act). To act upon something.\n'Der Arzt behandelt den Patienten.'",example:"A: Wer hat Sie behandelt?\nB: Doktor M\u00fcller hat mich behandelt.\nA: Wie war die Behandlung?\nB: Sehr professionell. Ich bin zufrieden.",exampleSrc:"A: Who treated you?\nB: Doctor M\u00fcller treated me.\nA: How was the treatment?\nB: Very professional. I am satisfied.",funFact:"To act upon something with your hands. 'Der Arzt behandelt den Patienten' (The doctor treats the patient). Also used for topics: 'Das Buch behandelt die Geschichte.' Handle and treat in one verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"finanziell",src:"financial",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From French 'financiel.'\nThe -iell ending marks French-origin adjectives.",example:"A: Hast du finanzielle Probleme?\nB: Nein, aber die Versicherung ist teuer.\nA: Finanzielle Planung ist wichtig.\nB: Da hast du recht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have financial problems?\nB: No, but the insurance is expensive.\nA: Financial planning is important.\nB: You are right about that.",funFact:"The -iell ending marks French-origin adjectives in German. 'Finanzielle Probleme' (financial problems) is why Verumius stares at his Krankenkasse letters with despair."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"comedic-despair",art:"de-ber-kitchen-papers",trg:"Die Briefe, \u00fcber die Verumius sich beschwert, sind alle auf Beamtendeutsch geschrieben. Das ist die Sprache, in der Formulare leben und Hoffnung stirbt.",src:"The letters Verumius complains about are all written in bureaucratic German. That is the language in which forms live and hope dies."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius hustet, hat Fieber und einen Schnupfen. Welches deutsche Wort beschreibt diese Krankheit?",opts:["Verletzung","Erk\u00e4ltung","Therapie","Operation"],ans:"Erk\u00e4ltung",hint:"This word comes from 'kalt' (cold) and describes a common illness."},
{type:"fb",s:"Im {1} ruft man die Nummer 112 an.",a:["Notfall"],opts:["Notfall","Notruf","Klinik","Kosten"],hint:"Which compound word means an emergency case?",sSrc:"In an emergency, you call the number 112."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Versicherung",src:"insurance"},{trg:"Untersuchung",src:"examination"},{trg:"Notaufnahme",src:"emergency room"},{trg:"Krankenwagen",src:"ambulance"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"ominous-comedy",art:"de-ber-kitchen-papers",trg:"Verumius schiebt die Briefe zur Seite. Morgen wird er KD anrufen. KD kennt sich aus. KD ist vom Amt. Und KD hat eine Telefonnummer, die tats\u00e4chlich funktioniert.",src:"Verumius pushes the letters aside. Tomorrow he will call KD. KD knows his way around. KD is from the government office. And KD has a phone number that actually works."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 2: "K\u00f6rpervokabular" — Vocab teach (20 words, 24 steps)
// Pure vocabulary: body parts, symptoms, sensations
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l2",title:"K\u00f6rpervokabular",icon:"🦴",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"K\u00f6rpervokabular",desc:"K\u00f6rperteile, Symptome und k\u00f6rperliche Empfindungen. Alles, was du brauchst, um dem Arzt deine Probleme zu erkl\u00e4ren.",goals:["Lerne K\u00f6rperteile auf Deutsch","Meistere W\u00f6rter f\u00fcr Symptome und Empfindungen","Beschreibe Gesundheitsprobleme auf Deutsch"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"comedy",art:"de-ber-arztpraxis",trg:"Verumius sitzt im Wartezimmer. Die \u00c4rztin ruft ihn auf. 'Was fehlt Ihnen?' Er zeigt auf seinen Bauch, dann auf seinen Kopf, dann auf sein Knie. Die \u00c4rztin wartet geduldig. 'Vielleicht sollten wir mit einem K\u00f6rperteil anfangen.'",src:"Verumius sits in the waiting room. The doctor calls him in. 'What is wrong with you?' He points at his stomach, then at his head, then at his knee. The doctor waits patiently. 'Maybe we should start with one body part.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Brust",src:"the chest, the breast",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Proto-Germanic *brustiz.\n'Brustschmerzen' = chest pains. Tell the Notarzt this one.",example:"A: Wo haben Sie Schmerzen?\nB: In der Brust. Es tut beim Atmen weh.\nA: Seit wann?\nB: Seit heute Morgen.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do you have pain?\nB: In the chest. It hurts when breathing.\nA: Since when?\nB: Since this morning.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'breast.' 'Brustschmerzen' (chest pains) is what you tell the Notarzt. Die Brust covers the entire chest area in medical German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Schulter",src:"the shoulder",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Cognate with English 'shoulder.'\n'Die kalte Schulter zeigen' = to give the cold shoulder.",example:"A: Meine Schulter tut weh.\nB: Die linke oder die rechte?\nA: Die rechte Schulter.\nB: Bewegen Sie den Arm mal nach oben.",exampleSrc:"A: My shoulder hurts.\nB: The left or the right one?\nA: The right shoulder.\nB: Move your arm upward.",funFact:"'Die kalte Schulter zeigen' (to give the cold shoulder) exists in German too. Same idiom, same body part, same meaning across both languages."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Knie",src:"the knee",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter. Pronounced with a spoken K.\nUnlike English, the K is NOT silent in German.",example:"A: Tut das Knie noch weh?\nB: Ja, besonders beim Treppensteigen.\nA: Legen Sie K\u00fchlpacks auf das Knie.\nB: Wie oft am Tag?",exampleSrc:"A: Does the knee still hurt?\nB: Yes, especially when climbing stairs.\nA: Put ice packs on the knee.\nB: How often per day?",funFact:"Pronounced 'k-nee' with a spoken K, unlike English where the K is silent. From Proto-Germanic *knewa-. Same root, different pronunciation fate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Finger",src:"the finger",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Identical spelling to English.\nFrom Proto-Germanic *fingraz.",example:"A: Was ist mit deinem Finger passiert?\nB: Ich habe ihn in der T\u00fcr eingeklemmt.\nA: Ist er gebrochen?\nB: Nein, nur gequetscht.",exampleSrc:"A: What happened to your finger?\nB: I caught it in the door.\nA: Is it broken?\nB: No, just bruised.",funFact:"Identical in spelling, nearly identical in pronunciation. 'Keinen Finger r\u00fchren' (to not lift a finger) works in both languages too."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Muskel",src:"the muscle",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'musculus' (little mouse).\nFlexing a muscle looks like a mouse under the skin.",example:"A: Mir tut jeder Muskel weh.\nB: Warst du im Fitnessstudio?\nA: Ja, ich habe zu viel trainiert.\nB: Muskelkater! Das geht in zwei Tagen weg.",exampleSrc:"A: Every muscle hurts.\nB: Were you at the gym?\nA: Yes, I trained too much.\nB: Muscle soreness! That goes away in two days.",funFact:"From Latin 'musculus' (little mouse). Flexing a muscle looks like a mouse running under the skin. Germans kept the Latin word, English shortened it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Knochen",src:"the bone",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Knochenbruch' = bone fracture.\n'Bis auf die Knochen' = to the bone (thoroughly).",example:"A: Ist der Knochen gebrochen?\nB: Nein, nur ein Riss.\nA: Wie lange dauert die Heilung?\nB: Etwa sechs Wochen f\u00fcr den Knochen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the bone broken?\nB: No, just a crack.\nA: How long does healing take?\nB: About six weeks for the bone.",funFact:"'Knochenbruch' (bone fracture) is a compound you can now decode: Knochen + Bruch (break). 'Bis auf die Knochen' (to the bone) means thoroughly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nase",src:"the nose",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Cognate with English 'nose.'\n'Die Nase voll haben' = to be fed up.",example:"A: Meine Nase l\u00e4uft die ganze Zeit.\nB: Hast du Schnupfen?\nA: Ja, seit gestern. Und ich kann nichts riechen.\nB: Nimm Nasentropfen.",exampleSrc:"A: My nose is running all the time.\nB: Do you have a cold?\nA: Yes, since yesterday. And I cannot smell anything.\nB: Take nose drops.",funFact:"'Die Nase voll haben' (to have a full nose) means to be fed up. Also: 'Schnupfen' is a stuffy nose. Germans have a word for every nasal condition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lippe",src:"the lip",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Cognate with English 'lip.'\n'Lippenbekenntnis' = lip service (false promise).",example:"A: Meine Lippen sind total trocken.\nB: Hier, nimm diesen Lippenbalsam.\nA: Danke! Trockene Lippen im Winter sind nervig.\nB: Ja, besonders bei K\u00e4lte.",exampleSrc:"A: My lips are totally dry.\nB: Here, take this lip balm.\nA: Thanks! Dry lips in winter are annoying.\nB: Yes, especially in the cold.",funFact:"'Lippenbekenntnis' (lip confession) means lip service. Germans say it when someone promises something but does not mean it. The lips move but the heart stays still."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Haut",src:"the skin",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Cognate with English 'hide' (animal skin).\n'Hautarzt' = dermatologist.",example:"A: Meine Haut ist ganz rot.\nB: Haben Sie eine Allergie?\nA: Vielleicht. Es juckt auch.\nB: Gehen Sie zum Hautarzt.",exampleSrc:"A: My skin is completely red.\nB: Do you have an allergy?\nA: Maybe. It also itches.\nB: Go to the dermatologist.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'hide' (animal skin). 'Aus der Haut fahren' (to drive out of one's skin) means to lose one's temper. 'Hautarzt' = dermatologist."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Atem",src:"the breath",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Atem holen' = to catch one's breath.\n'Atemlos' = breathless.",example:"A: Mir fehlt der Atem.\nB: Setzen Sie sich hin und atmen Sie tief.\nA: Ich bekomme kaum Atem.\nB: Wir rufen einen Arzt.",exampleSrc:"A: I cannot catch my breath.\nB: Sit down and breathe deeply.\nA: I can barely get air.\nB: We will call a doctor.",funFact:"Sanskrit 'atman' (breath/soul) is a distant cousin. Your breath, your spirit, your life force. All one ancient root. 'Atemlos' (breathless) works literally and figuratively."},
{type:"teach",trg:"atmen",src:"to breathe",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Atem. Regular verb.\n'Tief atmen' = to breathe deeply.",example:"A: Atmen Sie tief ein.\nB: So?\nA: Ja, und jetzt langsam ausatmen.\nB: Okay. Einatmen, ausatmen.",exampleSrc:"A: Breathe in deeply.\nB: Like this?\nA: Yes, and now breathe out slowly.\nB: Okay. Breathe in, breathe out.",funFact:"The doctor says 'Atmen Sie tief ein' (Breathe in deeply) during every Untersuchung. Einatmen (breathe in), ausatmen (breathe out). German splits breathing into directions."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bluten",src:"to bleed",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'Blut' (blood). Regular verb.\nCognate with English 'bleed/blood.'",example:"A: Die Wunde blutet stark!\nB: Dr\u00fccken Sie ein Tuch darauf.\nA: Wie lange soll ich dr\u00fccken?\nB: Bis es aufh\u00f6rt zu bluten.",exampleSrc:"A: The wound is bleeding heavily!\nB: Press a cloth onto it.\nA: How long should I press?\nB: Until it stops bleeding.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'bleed/blood.' 'Mein Herz blutet' (My heart bleeds) for emotional pain works in German too."},
{type:"teach",trg:"röntgen",src:"to X-ray",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Wilhelm Röntgen, who discovered X-rays in 1895.\nOnly used informally as a verb: 'Wir müssen röntgen.'",example:"A: Müssen wir röntgen?\nB: Ja, um sicher zu gehen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do we need to take an X-ray?\nB: Yes, to be sure.",funFact:"Named after Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen, a German physicist. He discovered X-rays in 1895 and won the first Nobel Prize in Physics in 1901. Germans call X-rays 'Röntgenstrahlen' (Röntgen rays)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Blutdruck",src:"the blood pressure",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Blut (blood) + Druck (pressure). Masculine.\nNormaler Blutdruck: 120/80.",example:"A: Wie ist mein Blutdruck?\nB: Normal. 120 zu 80.",exampleSrc:"A: How is my blood pressure?\nB: Normal. 120 over 80.",funFact:"Germany has one of the highest rates of high blood pressure in Europe. Regular Blutdruckmessen (blood pressure checks) are part of annual checkups. Blood pressure machines are found in many pharmacies."},
{type:"teach",trg:"brechen",src:"to break",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: bricht, brach, gebrochen.\nAlso: 'erbrechen' = to vomit (to break out).",example:"A: Ich glaube, ich habe mir den Arm gebrochen.\nB: K\u00f6nnen Sie den Arm bewegen?\nA: Nein, es tut furchtbar weh.\nB: Wir m\u00fcssen r\u00f6ntgen.",exampleSrc:"A: I think I broke my arm.\nB: Can you move the arm?\nA: No, it hurts terribly.\nB: We need to take an X-ray.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'break.' 'Sich den Arm brechen' (to break one's arm). Also: 'erbrechen' = to vomit (to break out). A versatile verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"messen",src:"to measure",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: misst, ma\u00df, gemessen.\n'Fieber messen' = to take a temperature.",example:"A: Wir m\u00fcssen Ihren Blutdruck messen.\nB: Ist der zu hoch?\nA: Mal sehen. Bitte den Arm ausstrecken.\nB: So? Wie hoch ist er?",exampleSrc:"A: We need to measure your blood pressure.\nB: Is it too high?\nA: Let's see. Please extend your arm.\nB: Like this? How high is it?",funFact:"'Fieber messen' (to take a temperature). 'Blutdruck messen' (to measure blood pressure). From the same root as English 'measure' via Latin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sp\u00fcren",src:"to feel, to sense",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Physical sensation, not emotional.\nDifferent from 'f\u00fchlen' (emotional feeling).",example:"A: Sp\u00fcren Sie den Schmerz hier?\nB: Ja, ich sp\u00fcre einen stechenden Schmerz.\nA: Und hier?\nB: Nein, da sp\u00fcre ich nichts.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel the pain here?\nB: Yes, I feel a stabbing pain.\nA: And here?\nB: No, I do not feel anything there.",funFact:"Different from 'f\u00fchlen' (emotional feeling). Sp\u00fcren is physical sensation. The Spur (trace/track) is related: what you can physically detect."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schwitzen",src:"to sweat",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From 'Schwei\u00df' (sweat).\n'Ins Schwitzen kommen' = to start sweating.",example:"A: Warum schwitzen Sie so?\nB: Ich habe Fieber und schwitze die ganze Nacht.\nA: Trinken Sie viel Wasser.\nB: Ja, das mache ich.",exampleSrc:"A: Why are you sweating so much?\nB: I have a fever and sweat all night.\nA: Drink lots of water.\nB: Yes, I am doing that.",funFact:"Germans love their saunas, where schwitzen is the whole point. 'Ins Schwitzen kommen' (to start sweating) also means getting nervous about something."},
{type:"teach",trg:"frieren",src:"to freeze, to be cold",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: fror, gefroren.\n'Mich friert' or 'Ich friere' both mean 'I am cold.'",example:"A: Frierst du?\nB: Ja, mir ist eiskalt.\nA: Hier, nimm meine Jacke.\nB: Danke! Ich friere seit einer Stunde.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you cold?\nB: Yes, I am freezing.\nA: Here, take my jacket.\nB: Thanks! I have been freezing for an hour.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'freeze.' The impersonal 'Mich friert' is older and more formal. 'Ich friere' is the everyday version. Both are correct."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"frustrated",art:"de-ber-arztpraxis",trg:"Die \u00c4rztin fragt: 'K\u00f6nnen Sie den Schmerz beschreiben? Stechend, dumpf oder brennend?' Verumius kennt keines dieser W\u00f6rter. Er macht Ger\u00e4usche. Die \u00c4rztin schreibt 'unspezifisch' in die Akte.",src:"The doctor asks: 'Can you describe the pain? Stabbing, dull, or burning?' Verumius does not know any of these words. He makes noises. The doctor writes 'unspecific' in the file."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ersch\u00f6pft",src:"exhausted",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'ersch\u00f6pfen' (to exhaust).\nStronger than 'm\u00fcde' (tired). Drained out.",example:"A: Du siehst ersch\u00f6pft aus.\nB: Ich bin total ersch\u00f6pft. Die ganze Woche war stressig.\nA: Du solltest dich ausruhen.\nB: Ja, ich lege mich gleich hin.",exampleSrc:"A: You look exhausted.\nB: I am totally exhausted. The whole week was stressful.\nA: You should rest.\nB: Yes, I will lie down right away.",funFact:"Literally 'drained out' (the Sch\u00f6pf- root relates to scooping/drawing water). Stronger than 'm\u00fcde' (tired). When m\u00fcde is not enough, you are ersch\u00f6pft."},
{type:"teach",trg:"blass",src:"pale",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Blass werden' = to turn pale.\n'Blass vor Neid' = pale with envy.",example:"A: Du bist ganz blass. Geht es dir gut?\nB: Ich f\u00fchle mich nicht so gut.\nA: Setz dich hin. Du siehst wirklich blass aus.\nB: Ja, mir ist auch schwindelig.",exampleSrc:"A: You are very pale. Are you alright?\nB: I do not feel so well.\nA: Sit down. You really look pale.\nB: Yes, I also feel dizzy.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'blaze' through a surprising twist: original meaning was 'shining/white.' The paleness of bright light became the paleness of illness."},
{type:"teach",trg:"k\u00f6rperlich",src:"physical, bodily",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'K\u00f6rper' (body) + -lich.\n'K\u00f6rperliche Arbeit' = physical labor.",example:"A: Machen Sie k\u00f6rperliche Arbeit?\nB: Ja, ich arbeite auf einer Baustelle.\nA: Haben Sie k\u00f6rperliche Beschwerden?\nB: Ja, R\u00fcckenschmerzen und M\u00fcdigkeit.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you do physical work?\nB: Yes, I work at a construction site.\nA: Do you have physical complaints?\nB: Yes, back pain and fatigue.",funFact:"The -lich ending turns nouns into adjectives. 'K\u00f6rperlich und geistig' (physically and mentally) is a common pair in German medical contexts."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Arzt bittet dich, den Arm zu heben. Aber zuerst: Wie hei\u00dft das Gelenk zwischen Ober- und Unterschenkel?",opts:["Schulter","Finger","Knie","Brust"],ans:"Knie",hint:"This joint bends when you sit. In German, the K is pronounced."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Patient ist sehr {1}. Er hat kein Blut mehr im Gesicht.",a:["blass"],opts:["blass","ersch\u00f6pft","k\u00f6rperlich","finanziell"],hint:"Which adjective describes someone who has lost color in their face?",sSrc:"The patient is very pale. He has no more blood in his face."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"atmen",src:"to breathe"},{trg:"bluten",src:"to bleed"},{trg:"frieren",src:"to freeze"},{trg:"schwitzen",src:"to sweat"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-arztpraxis",trg:"Die \u00c4rztin gibt Verumius ein Rezept und sagt: 'Gute Besserung.' Er versteht das Wort sofort. Besser werden. Besserung. Deutsch ist logisch, wenn man die Teile kennt.",src:"The doctor gives Verumius a prescription and says: 'Get well soon.' He understands the word immediately. To get better. Improvement. German is logical when you know the parts."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 3: "KD im Caf\u00e9" — Story dev + grammar (18 words, 22 steps)
// Scene 2: KD off-duty at cafe, relative clauses + prepositions
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l3",title:"KD im Caf\u00e9",icon:"☕",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"KD im Caf\u00e9",desc:"KD sitzt in Jeans und Pullover im Caf\u00e9. Er liest die Versicherungsbriefe wie Kinderb\u00fccher. Heute lernst du Finanz- und Zahlungsvokabeln.",goals:["Lerne Finanz- und Zahlungsvokabeln","Verstehe Relativs\u00e4tze mit Pr\u00e4positionen","Erlebe KD als Mensch, nicht nur als Beamter"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"kd",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"Also, zeig mal her. Die Briefe, \u00fcber die du dich beschwerst, sind eigentlich ganz einfach. Das ist nur Beamtendeutsch.",src:"Alright, let me see. The letters you are complaining about are actually quite simple. That is just bureaucratic German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Versichertenkarte",src:"the health insurance card",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Versicherte (insured person) + Karte (card).\nBring it to every doctor visit.",example:"A: Haben Sie Ihre Versichertenkarte dabei?\nB: Ja, hier bitte.\nA: Danke. Bitte im Wartezimmer Platz nehmen.\nB: Wie lange muss ich warten?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have your insurance card with you?\nB: Yes, here you go.\nA: Thank you. Please take a seat in the waiting room.\nB: How long do I have to wait?",funFact:"Your health insurance card. Without it, you pay upfront. The electronic Gesundheitskarte replaced the old paper version in 2015. Always carry it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zahlung",src:"the payment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'zahlen' (to pay) + -ung.\n'Monatliche Zahlung' = monthly payment.",example:"A: Die Zahlung ist f\u00e4llig.\nB: Wann muss ich bezahlen?\nA: Bis zum 15. des Monats.\nB: Kann ich per \u00dcberweisung zahlen?",exampleSrc:"A: The payment is due.\nB: When do I have to pay?\nA: By the 15th of the month.\nB: Can I pay by bank transfer?",funFact:"'Zahlungserinnerung' (payment reminder) is the polite version of a Mahnung. The -ung suffix creates the noun from the verb. Standard German word-building."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mahnung",src:"the payment reminder, the warning",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'mahnen' (to warn/remind).\nThree levels: polite, firm, legal action.",example:"A: Ich habe eine Mahnung bekommen!\nB: Die erste oder die zweite?\nA: Die zweite.\nB: Dann musst du schnell bezahlen.",exampleSrc:"A: I received a payment reminder!\nB: The first or the second one?\nA: The second one.\nB: Then you need to pay quickly.",funFact:"The first Mahnung is polite. The second is firm. The third threatens legal action. Germans take Mahnungen extremely seriously. Do not ignore them."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ausgabe",src:"the expenditure, the expense",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Aus (out) + Gabe (giving). Money going out.\nOpposite of Einnahme (income).",example:"A: Wie hoch sind deine monatlichen Ausgaben?\nB: Etwa 1500 Euro.\nA: Das sind hohe Ausgaben.\nB: Ja, die Miete allein kostet 800 Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: How high are your monthly expenses?\nB: About 1500 euros.\nA: Those are high expenses.\nB: Yes, the rent alone costs 800 euros.",funFact:"Money going out. The opposite of Einnahme (income). Also means 'edition' (Ausgabe eines Buchs). Context decides whether it is money or books."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erh\u00f6hung",src:"the increase, the raise",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'erh\u00f6hen' (to increase/raise).\nCompound with everything: Beitrags-, Miet-, Lohnerh\u00f6hung.",example:"A: Es gibt eine Beitragserh\u00f6hung.\nB: Schon wieder? Um wie viel?\nA: Um 0,5 Prozent.\nB: Das ist doch eine kleine Erh\u00f6hung.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a premium increase.\nB: Again? By how much?\nA: By 0.5 percent.\nB: That is just a small increase.",funFact:"Germans compound Erh\u00f6hung with everything that costs money. Beitragserh\u00f6hung (premium increase), Mieterh\u00f6hung (rent increase), Lohnerh\u00f6hung (pay raise). The word that never stops compounding."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Summe",src:"the sum, the total",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'summa.' International, mathematical.\n'In Summe' = in total.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist die Summe?\nB: Die Summe betr\u00e4gt 3.500 Euro.\nA: Das ist eine hohe Summe.\nB: Ja, aber sie beinhaltet alles.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is the total?\nB: The total amounts to 3,500 euros.\nA: That is a large sum.\nB: Yes, but it includes everything.",funFact:"From Latin 'summa.' Simple, international, mathematical. Even the Romans did their Summen. 'In Summe' (in total) works in business and everyday speech."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Steuer",src:"the tax",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'Einkommensteuer' = income tax.\n'Mehrwertsteuer' = VAT. Germany's tax system is famously complex.",example:"A: Wie viel Steuer zahlst du?\nB: Viel zu viel! Fast 40 Prozent.\nA: Die Steuer in Deutschland ist hoch.\nB: Ja, aber daf\u00fcr funktioniert das System.",exampleSrc:"A: How much tax do you pay?\nB: Way too much! Almost 40 percent.\nA: The tax in Germany is high.\nB: Yes, but the system works because of it.",funFact:"From Old High German 'stiura' (support/contribution). 'Steuererkl\u00e4rung' (tax return) is an annual ritual. Germany's tax system is famously complex."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Lohn",src:"the wage, the salary",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Mindestlohn' = minimum wage.\nDifferent from 'Gehalt' (monthly salary, white-collar).",example:"A: Wie hoch ist der Mindestlohn?\nB: 12,41 Euro pro Stunde.\nA: Reicht der Lohn zum Leben?\nB: In Berlin ist es knapp.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is the minimum wage?\nB: 12.41 euros per hour.\nA: Is the wage enough to live on?\nB: In Berlin it is tight.",funFact:"Different from 'Gehalt' (monthly salary for white-collar workers). Lohn is traditionally for hourly/manual work. The distinction is fading in modern German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"berechnen",src:"to calculate, to charge",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + rechnen (to calculate).\nCalculation and billing in one verb.",example:"A: K\u00f6nnen Sie die Kosten berechnen?\nB: Ja, ich berechne alles f\u00fcr Sie.\nA: Was berechnen Sie f\u00fcr die Untersuchung?\nB: Das berechnen wir \u00fcber die Krankenkasse.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you calculate the costs?\nB: Yes, I will calculate everything for you.\nA: What do you charge for the examination?\nB: We charge that through the health insurance.",funFact:"'Die Kosten berechnen' (to calculate the costs). Also: 'Dem Kunden etwas berechnen' (to charge the customer for something). Calculation and billing in one verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"finanzieren",src:"to finance",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From French 'financer.' The -ieren ending = borrowed verb.\nRegular, predictable, international.",example:"A: Wie finanzierst du dein Studium?\nB: Meine Eltern finanzieren es teilweise.\nA: Und den Rest?\nB: Den finanziere ich mit einem Nebenjob.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you finance your studies?\nB: My parents finance it partly.\nA: And the rest?\nB: I finance that with a part-time job.",funFact:"The -ieren ending marks it as a borrowed verb. Regular, predictable, international. 'Wie finanzierst du das?' (How do you finance that?) is a common German question."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einnahme",src:"the income, the revenue",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ein (in) + Nahme (taking). Money coming in.\nAlso: 'Einnahme von Medizin' = taking medicine.",example:"A: Wie sind Ihre monatlichen Einnahmen?\nB: Meine Einnahmen betragen 2.500 Euro netto.\nA: Und die Ausgaben?\nB: Etwa 1.800 Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your monthly income?\nB: My income is 2,500 euros net.\nA: And the expenses?\nB: About 1,800 euros.",funFact:"The opposite of Ausgabe. Money coming in, medicine going in. 'Einnahme von Medizin' = taking medicine. Same word for money and medicine intake."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Einkauf",src:"the purchase, the shopping",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Ein (in) + Kauf (purchase).\n'Eink\u00e4ufe machen' = to do shopping.",example:"A: Ich muss noch Eink\u00e4ufe machen.\nB: Was brauchst du?\nA: Nur den t\u00e4glichen Einkauf. Brot, Milch, Gem\u00fcse.\nB: Soll ich mitkommen?",exampleSrc:"A: I still need to do shopping.\nB: What do you need?\nA: Just the daily shopping. Bread, milk, vegetables.\nB: Should I come along?",funFact:"The Einkaufswagen (shopping cart) is where German compounds shine. Ein (in) + Kauf (purchase) + Wagen (cart). Three words, one object."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kauf",src:"the purchase",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'kaufen' (to buy).\n'Kaufvertrag' = purchase contract. Short, sharp, commercial.",example:"A: War das ein guter Kauf?\nB: Ja, ein sehr guter Kauf.\nA: Wie viel hast du bezahlt?\nB: Nur 50 Euro. Ein echtes Schn\u00e4ppchen.",exampleSrc:"A: Was that a good purchase?\nB: Yes, a very good purchase.\nA: How much did you pay?\nB: Only 50 euros. A real bargain.",funFact:"Short, sharp, commercial. 'Ein guter Kauf' (a good buy). 'Kaufvertrag' (purchase contract). Every transaction is a Kauf."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Gewinn",src:"the profit, the winnings",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'gewinnen' (to win).\n'Gewinn machen' = to make a profit.",example:"A: Hat die Firma Gewinn gemacht?\nB: Ja, der Gewinn war h\u00f6her als letztes Jahr.\nA: Wie hoch war der Gewinn?\nB: Fast eine Million Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company make a profit?\nB: Yes, the profit was higher than last year.\nA: How high was the profit?\nB: Almost one million euros.",funFact:"The Ge- prefix plus -nn creates the noun from the verb. 'Lottogewinn' (lottery winnings). Standard German word-formation pattern."},
{type:"story",speaker:"kd",mood:"casual",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"KD bestellt noch einen Kaffee. Ohne Uniform sieht er aus wie ein normaler Mensch. 'Die Formulare, \u00fcber die alle sich aufregen, schreibe nicht ich,' sagt er. 'Ich \u00fcbersetze sie nur.' Verumius fragt: 'Wer schreibt sie dann?' KD zuckt die Achseln. 'Niemand weiss das.'",src:"KD orders another coffee. Without his uniform he looks like a normal person. 'The forms everyone gets upset about, I do not write them,' he says. 'I only translate them.' Verumius asks: 'Who writes them then?' KD shrugs. 'Nobody knows.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"niedrig",src:"low",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'nieder' (down).\n'Niedrig' for measurable things, 'tief' for depth and emotion.",example:"A: Die Kosten sind relativ niedrig.\nB: Wirklich? Wie niedrig?\nA: Nur 150 Euro pro Monat.\nB: Das ist tats\u00e4chlich niedrig.",exampleSrc:"A: The costs are relatively low.\nB: Really? How low?\nA: Only 150 euros per month.\nB: That is indeed low.",funFact:"'Niedrig' for measurable things (costs, blood pressure, temperature), 'tief' for depth and emotion. From 'nieder' (down). Two words for 'low' with different domains."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gering",src:"small, slight, minor",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"More formal than 'niedrig.'\n'Nicht im Geringsten' = not in the slightest.",example:"A: Sind die Risiken gering?\nB: Ja, nur ein geringes Risiko.\nA: Dann mache ich es.\nB: Die Kosten sind auch gering.",exampleSrc:"A: Are the risks minor?\nB: Yes, only a minor risk.\nA: Then I will do it.\nB: The costs are also minor.",funFact:"More formal than 'niedrig.' Used for quantities and importance, not physical size. 'Nicht im Geringsten' (not in the slightest) is a useful intensifier."},
{type:"teach",trg:"knapp",src:"tight, scarce, barely",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Knapp bei Kasse' = tight on money.\n'Knapp gewonnen' = barely won.",example:"A: Hast du genug Geld?\nB: Es ist knapp. Sehr knapp.\nA: Reicht es f\u00fcr die Versicherung?\nB: Gerade so. Knapp, aber es reicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have enough money?\nB: It is tight. Very tight.\nA: Is it enough for the insurance?\nB: Just barely. Tight, but it is enough.",funFact:"A word that squeezes everything: time, money, space. If it is knapp, there is almost not enough. 'Knapp bei Kasse' (tight on money) is the student's motto."},
{type:"tip",title:"Relativs\u00e4tze mit Pr\u00e4positionen",text:"In German, prepositions stay with the relative pronoun. In English, you might say 'the letter I am complaining ABOUT.' In German, the preposition comes FIRST:\n\nDer Brief, \u00dcBER DEN ich mich beschwere.\n\nFormula: Noun, + PREPOSITION + RELATIVE PRONOUN + ... verb at end.\n\nThe relative pronoun matches:\n- Gender from the noun it refers to\n- Case from the preposition\n\nExamples:\n- Die Karte, MIT DER du zum Arzt gehst (mit + dative, die = feminine)\n- Der Brief, \u00dcBER DEN du dich beschwerst (\u00fcber + accusative, der = masculine)\n- Das Formular, AUF DAS ich warte (auf + accusative, das = neuter)",deepDive:{title:"How to build relative clauses with prepositions",text:"Step 1: Identify the preposition the verb needs (sich beschweren \u00dcBER, warten AUF, sich entscheiden F\u00dcR).\n\nStep 2: Determine the case the preposition requires (accusative or dative).\n\nStep 3: Match the relative pronoun to the gender of the noun AND the case from the preposition.\n\nDer Brief (\u00fcber + acc, masculine) = \u00fcber den\nDie Karte (mit + dat, feminine) = mit der\nDas Formular (auf + acc, neuter) = auf das\n\nThe verb always goes to the end of the relative clause."}},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"surprised",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"KD faltet einen Brief auseinander und liest vor: 'Ihr Antrag auf Erstattung der Zuzahlung gem\u00e4\u00df Paragraph 62 SGB V...' Er \u00fcbersetzt: 'Du bekommst Geld zur\u00fcck.' Verumius starrt ihn an. 'Das steht da? In diesen drei Zeilen?'",src:"KD unfolds a letter and reads aloud: 'Your application for reimbursement of the co-payment in accordance with Section 62 SGB V...' He translates: 'You are getting money back.' Verumius stares at him. 'That is what it says? In those three lines?'"},
{type:"mc",q:"KD sagt: 'Die Versicherung, bei der du versichert bist, ist gut.' Was bedeutet 'bei der'?",opts:["the doctor","the hospital","the card","the insurance company"],ans:"the insurance company",hint:"The relative pronoun 'der' is feminine dative, matching 'die Versicherung.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Die monatliche {1} f\u00fcr die Versicherung betr\u00e4gt 200 Euro.",a:["Zahlung"],opts:["Zahlung","Mahnung","Ausgabe","Erh\u00f6hung"],hint:"Which noun specifically means a regular payment?",sSrc:"The monthly payment for the insurance amounts to 200 euros."},
{type:"story",speaker:"kd",mood:"satisfied",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"KD stapelt die Briefe ordentlich. 'Der Stapel, vor dem du Angst hattest, sind eigentlich nur f\u00fcnf verschiedene Briefe. Den Rest kannst du wegwerfen.' Verumius f\u00fchlt sich leichter. Also war das Chaos nur Wiederholungen.",src:"KD stacks the letters neatly. 'The pile you were afraid of is actually only five different letters. You can throw the rest away.' Verumius feels lighter. So the chaos was just duplicates."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 4: "Die Grammatik der B\u00fcrokratie" — Grammar (18 words, 24 steps)
// Grammar: #11 Relative clauses + prepositions, #33 Adverbial conjunctions
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l4",title:"Die Grammatik der B\u00fcrokratie",icon:"📐",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Grammatik der B\u00fcrokratie",desc:"Zwei wichtige Grammatikstrukturen: Relativs\u00e4tze mit Pr\u00e4positionen und Adverbialkonjunktionen. Medizinvokabeln verbinden beides.",goals:["Meistere Relativs\u00e4tze mit Pr\u00e4positionen","Lerne Adverbialkonjunktionen: deshalb, trotzdem, deswegen, also, sonst","Verbinde Medizinvokabeln mit Grammatikstrukturen"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"kd",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"KD trinkt seinen Kaffee und sagt: 'Weisst du, warum deutsche S\u00e4tze so lang sind? Weil das Verb am Ende steht. Deshalb versteht man erst am Schluss, was gemeint ist.' Er grinst. 'Willkommen in der Grammatik.'",src:"KD drinks his coffee and says: 'Do you know why German sentences are so long? Because the verb goes at the end. That is why you only understand at the very end what is meant.' He grins. 'Welcome to the grammar.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Pflaster",src:"the bandage, the plaster",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'emplastrum.'\nAlso means 'pavement' (Kopfsteinpflaster = cobblestone).",example:"A: Hast du ein Pflaster?\nB: Ja, hier. Gro\u00df oder klein?\nA: Ein gro\u00dfes Pflaster bitte.\nB: Hier, kleb es auf die Wunde.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a bandage?\nB: Yes, here. Large or small?\nA: A large bandage please.\nB: Here, stick it on the wound.",funFact:"From Latin 'emplastrum.' Also means 'pavement' (Kopfsteinpflaster = cobblestone). Two very different surfaces that share a word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Salbe",src:"the ointment, the salve",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Cognate with English 'salve.'\nFrom Latin 'salvare' (to save/heal).",example:"A: Diese Salbe hilft gegen Schmerzen.\nB: Wie oft soll ich die Salbe auftragen?\nA: Zweimal am Tag.\nB: Morgens und abends?",exampleSrc:"A: This ointment helps against pain.\nB: How often should I apply the ointment?\nA: Twice a day.\nB: Morning and evening?",funFact:"Cognate with English 'salve.' From Latin 'salvare' (to save/heal). One of the oldest medicine words in Germanic languages. Apply to Haut for relief."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pille",src:"the pill",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'pilula' (little ball).\n'Die Pille' alone usually means the contraceptive pill.",example:"A: Nehmen Sie diese Pillen dreimal t\u00e4glich.\nB: Vor oder nach dem Essen?\nA: Nach dem Essen. Mit Wasser.\nB: Wie lange soll ich sie nehmen?",exampleSrc:"A: Take these pills three times daily.\nB: Before or after eating?\nA: After eating. With water.\nB: How long should I take them?",funFact:"'Die Pille' by itself usually means the contraceptive pill. For other pills: 'Tablette' or 'Pille gegen Kopfschmerzen.' Context-dependent social meaning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Spritze",src:"the injection, the syringe",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'spritzen' (to spray/squirt).\n'Spritzenphobie' is a real diagnosis.",example:"A: Ich brauche eine Spritze gegen die Schmerzen.\nB: Haben Sie Angst vor Spritzen?\nA: Ein bisschen.\nB: Keine Sorge, es dauert nur eine Sekunde.",exampleSrc:"A: I need an injection for the pain.\nB: Are you afraid of injections?\nA: A little.\nB: Don't worry, it only takes a second.",funFact:"Germans fear the Spritze more than most medical procedures. 'Spritzenphobie' is a real diagnosis. From 'spritzen' (to spray/squirt)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Tropfen",src:"the drop",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Augentropfen' = eye drops, 'Nasentropfen' = nose drops.\nAlso the verb 'tropfen' (to drip).",example:"A: Nehmen Sie diese Tropfen dreimal am Tag.\nB: Wie viele Tropfen?\nA: Zehn Tropfen in ein Glas Wasser.\nB: Vor oder nach dem Essen?",exampleSrc:"A: Take these drops three times a day.\nB: How many drops?\nA: Ten drops in a glass of water.\nB: Before or after eating?",funFact:"'Ein Tropfen auf den hei\u00dfen Stein' (a drop on a hot stone) means a futile effort. The drop evaporates before it can help. A beautifully pessimistic idiom."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Schmerzmittel",src:"the painkiller",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Schmerz (pain) + Mittel (means/remedy).\nTransparent compound: pain-means.",example:"A: Haben Sie ein Schmerzmittel?\nB: Ja, Ibuprofen oder Paracetamol?\nA: Was empfehlen Sie?\nB: Bei Kopfschmerzen: Ibuprofen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a painkiller?\nB: Yes, ibuprofen or paracetamol?\nA: What do you recommend?\nB: For headaches: ibuprofen.",funFact:"German compounds are transparent: pain-means. You always know what you are swallowing. 'Schmerzmittel einnehmen' (to take painkillers)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Schnupfen",src:"the cold, the runny nose",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'schnupfen' (to sniff).\nLess formal than Erk\u00e4ltung. Focuses on the nose.",example:"A: Hast du Schnupfen?\nB: Ja, meine Nase l\u00e4uft den ganzen Tag.\nA: Hier, nimm ein Taschentuch.\nB: Danke. Dieser Schnupfen geht nicht weg.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a cold?\nB: Yes, my nose is running all day.\nA: Here, take a tissue.\nB: Thanks. This cold won't go away.",funFact:"Schnupfen focuses on the nose; Erk\u00e4ltung is the whole-body cold. From 'schnupfen' (to sniff). Less formal, more specific."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Husten",src:"the cough",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Also the verb 'husten' (to cough).\n'Hustensirup' = cough syrup. Onomatopoeia.",example:"A: Wie lange haben Sie schon Husten?\nB: Seit einer Woche.\nA: Trockener Husten oder mit Schleim?\nB: Trockener Husten, besonders nachts.",exampleSrc:"A: How long have you had a cough?\nB: For a week.\nA: Dry cough or with mucus?\nB: Dry cough, especially at night.",funFact:"Onomatopoeia: the word sounds like a cough. Same root as English 'cough' before English changed its spelling. 'Hustensirup' (cough syrup) is a pharmacy staple."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Infektion",src:"the infection",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'infectio.'\nThe -tion ending is always feminine, always stressed on the last syllable.",example:"A: Es ist eine bakterielle Infektion.\nB: Brauche ich Antibiotika?\nA: Ja, ich verschreibe Ihnen welche.\nB: Wie lange dauert die Infektion?",exampleSrc:"A: It is a bacterial infection.\nB: Do I need antibiotics?\nA: Yes, I will prescribe some.\nB: How long does the infection last?",funFact:"Identical in most European languages. The -tion ending is always feminine in German, always stressed on the last syllable. A reliable pattern."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Virus",src:"the virus",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'virus' (poison).\nNeuter (das Virus), though some say 'der Virus.'",example:"A: Ist es ein Virus oder eine Infektion?\nB: Ein Virus. Antibiotika helfen nicht.\nA: Was soll ich tun?\nB: Ruhe, Fl\u00fcssigkeit und abwarten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is it a virus or an infection?\nB: A virus. Antibiotics won't help.\nA: What should I do?\nB: Rest, fluids, and wait it out.",funFact:"Neuter in German (das Virus), though some Germans say 'der Virus.' The Duden accepts both. Scientists insist on 'das.' A rare grammar debate in medicine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verschreiben",src:"to prescribe",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + schreiben (to write). The doctor writes for you.\n'Sich verschreiben' = to make a writing mistake.",example:"A: Der Arzt hat mir Tropfen verschrieben.\nB: Gegen was?\nA: Gegen die Infektion.\nB: Gut, nimm sie regelm\u00e4\u00dfig ein.",exampleSrc:"A: The doctor prescribed me drops.\nB: For what?\nA: For the infection.\nB: Good, take them regularly.",funFact:"The doctor writes something for you. 'Sich verschreiben' means to make a writing mistake. The ver- prefix changes everything. One letter, two very different meanings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einnehmen",src:"to take (medicine), to collect (money)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein + nehmen. Separable prefix.\n'Nehmen Sie die Tabletten zweimal t\u00e4glich ein.'",example:"A: Wie soll ich die Medizin einnehmen?\nB: Zweimal t\u00e4glich, morgens und abends.\nA: Vor oder nach dem Essen?\nB: Nach dem Essen einnehmen.",exampleSrc:"A: How should I take the medicine?\nB: Twice daily, morning and evening.\nA: Before or after eating?\nB: Take it after eating.",funFact:"Separable: 'Nehmen Sie die Tabletten zweimal t\u00e4glich ein.' Also: 'Einnahmen' (revenue). Medicine intake and money intake share a verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"operieren",src:"to operate (surgery)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'operari.' Regular: -ieren ending.\n'Am Knie operiert' = operated on the knee.",example:"A: Wir m\u00fcssen operieren.\nB: Ist die Operation gef\u00e4hrlich?\nA: Nein, ein Routineeingriff.\nB: Wann wird operiert?",exampleSrc:"A: We need to operate.\nB: Is the operation dangerous?\nA: No, a routine procedure.\nB: When will you operate?",funFact:"The -ieren ending makes it regular and predictable. 'Operiert werden' (to be operated on). A serious verb for a serious procedure."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die \u00c4rztin",src:"the doctor (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine of Arzt. The -in suffix is standard.\nModern: '\u00c4rzt*in' for inclusive forms.",example:"A: Die \u00c4rztin kommt gleich.\nB: Welche \u00c4rztin?\nA: Frau Dr. Weber. Sie ist sehr gut.\nB: Gut, ich warte.",exampleSrc:"A: The doctor will be right with you.\nB: Which doctor?\nA: Dr. Weber. She is very good.\nB: Good, I will wait.",funFact:"The feminine of Arzt. In modern German, many institutions use '\u00c4rzt*in' to be inclusive. The -in suffix is the standard feminine marker for person nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Doktorin",src:"the doctor (female, title)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine of Doktor.\n'Frau Doktor' is more common than 'Frau Doktorin.'",example:"A: Guten Tag, Frau Doktorin.\nB: Guten Tag. Was kann ich f\u00fcr Sie tun?\nA: Ich habe Bauchschmerzen.\nB: Seit wann?",exampleSrc:"A: Good day, Doctor.\nB: Good day. What can I do for you?\nA: I have a stomachache.\nB: Since when?",funFact:"'Frau Doktorin M\u00fcller' is extremely formal. Most people simply say 'Frau Doktor.' The -in is grammatically correct but socially optional with titles."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Schwierigkeit",src:"the difficulty",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'schwierig' (difficult) + -keit.\nAbstract noun from adjective.",example:"A: Haben Sie Schwierigkeiten mit dem Formular?\nB: Ja, ich verstehe Punkt 5 nicht.\nA: Das ist eine bekannte Schwierigkeit.\nB: Kann mir jemand helfen?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have difficulties with the form?\nB: Yes, I do not understand point 5.\nA: That is a known difficulty.\nB: Can someone help me?",funFact:"The -keit suffix turns adjectives into abstract nouns. 'Finanzielle Schwierigkeiten' (financial difficulties). The insurance letters are full of Schwierigkeiten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"maximal",src:"maximum, at most",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'maximus.'\n'Maximal zwei Tabletten pro Tag.'",example:"A: Wie viele Tabletten darf ich nehmen?\nB: Maximal drei pro Tag.\nA: Und wenn die Schmerzen schlimmer werden?\nB: Dann kommen Sie zur\u00fcck.",exampleSrc:"A: How many tablets am I allowed to take?\nB: Maximum three per day.\nA: And if the pain gets worse?\nB: Then come back.",funFact:"In insurance: 'maximale Erstattung' (maximum reimbursement). International, transparent, precise. From Latin 'maximus.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"minimal",src:"minimal, at least",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"The opposite of maximal.\n'Minimaler Aufwand, maximaler Effekt.'",example:"A: Wie gro\u00df ist das Risiko?\nB: Minimal. Wirklich sehr gering.\nA: Gibt es minimale Nebenwirkungen?\nB: Ja, nur minimale.",exampleSrc:"A: How big is the risk?\nB: Minimal. Really very low.\nA: Are there minimal side effects?\nB: Yes, only minimal.",funFact:"'Minimaler Aufwand, maximaler Effekt' (minimal effort, maximum effect). Insurance companies love this phrase. For them, not for you."},
{type:"teach",trg:"deswegen",src:"therefore, for that reason",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Des (of that) + wegen (because of). Synonym of deshalb.\nMain clause connector: verb in second position after it.",example:"A: Verumius war krank. Deswegen ging er zum Arzt.\nB: Hat der Arzt etwas verschrieben?\nA: Ja, deswegen geht es ihm besser.\nB: Gut, deswegen kann er morgen wiederkommen.",exampleSrc:"A: Verumius was sick. Therefore he went to the doctor.\nB: Did the doctor prescribe something?\nA: Yes, therefore he feels better.\nB: Good, therefore he can come back tomorrow.",funFact:"Deswegen, deshalb, daher, darum all mean therefore. Germans use them interchangeably. Deswegen literally breaks down to des (of that) + wegen (because of): because of that."},
{type:"tip",title:"Adverbialkonjunktionen: deshalb, trotzdem, deswegen, also, sonst",text:"These words connect two main clauses and show cause, contrast, or consequence. The verb comes IMMEDIATELY after them (V2 position).\n\nStructure: Main clause. Adverbial conjunction + VERB + subject + rest.\n\n- deshalb (therefore): Er ist krank. Deshalb geht er zum Arzt.\n- trotzdem (nevertheless): Es regnet. Trotzdem geht sie joggen.\n- deswegen (that is why): Die Kosten steigen. Deswegen zahlen wir mehr.\n- also (so/therefore): Du bist versichert. Also musst du dir keine Sorgen machen.\n- sonst (otherwise): Nimm die Medizin. Sonst wird es schlimmer.\n\nCompare with weil (subordinating): Er geht zum Arzt, weil er krank ist. (verb at END)\nVs. deshalb (adverbial): Er ist krank. Deshalb GEHT er zum Arzt. (verb after deshalb)",deepDive:{title:"Adverbial vs. subordinating conjunctions",text:"Subordinating conjunctions (weil, dass, obwohl, damit, falls) push the verb to the END of the clause:\nEr geht zum Arzt, weil er krank IST.\n\nAdverbial conjunctions (deshalb, trotzdem, deswegen, also, sonst) keep the verb in SECOND position:\nEr ist krank. Deshalb GEHT er zum Arzt.\n\nThe key difference: subordinating conjunctions create Nebens\u00e4tze (subordinate clauses). Adverbial conjunctions connect two Haupts\u00e4tze (main clauses). The word order tells you which type you are dealing with."}},
{type:"tip",title:"deshalb vs. trotzdem: Direction of Logic",text:"Both trigger inversion (verb in position 2), but with opposite logic:\n\ndeshalb = expected result (consequence):\nEs regnet. Deshalb bleibe ich zu Hause. (logical)\n\ntrotzdem = unexpected result (surprise):\nEs regnet. Trotzdem gehe ich raus. (unexpected)\n\ndeshalb = 'deswegen' / trotzdem = 'trotz dessen' (despite that)",deepDive:{title:"dennoch vs. trotzdem",text:"trotzdem = everyday speech\ndennoch = formal written language, essays, news\n\n'Der Markt fiel. Dennoch blieben die Anleger ruhig.'\n(The market fell. Nevertheless the investors remained calm.)\n\nIn conversation: trotzdem.\nIn an essay: dennoch."}},
{type:"tip",title:"obwohl vs. trotzdem: Grammar Difference",text:"obwohl = subordinating conjunction, verb goes to the END:\nObwohl es regnet, gehe ich raus.\n[Subclause: verb LAST] [Main clause: V2]\n\ntrotzdem = adverb, verb stays in position 2:\nEs regnet. Trotzdem gehe ich raus.\n[Main clause 1] [Main clause 2]\n\nSame meaning. Completely different grammar.\nTest: Can you start a new sentence with it? trotzdem YES, obwohl NO.",deepDive:{title:"Sentence Structure Comparison",text:"With obwohl (one complex sentence):\nObwohl es kalt ist, gehe ich schwimmen.\n[Subclause: verb at end] [Main clause: V2]\n\nWith trotzdem (two main clauses):\nEs ist kalt. Trotzdem gehe ich schwimmen.\n[Main clause 1] [Main clause 2: V2 after trotzdem]\n\nPractice converting:\nobwohl sentence to trotzdem sentence and vice versa."}},
{type:"tip",title:"Formality Scale: Adding Information",text:"From casual to formal:\n\nauch = also (simplest form)\naußerdem = moreover (everyday, versatile)\nzudem = furthermore (slightly formal)\ndarüber hinaus = beyond that (essays only)\n\nAll add new information. außerdem is the safe default.",deepDive:{title:"Word Order with außerdem",text:"Position 1 (with inversion):\nAußerdem spricht sie Französisch.\n\nMiddle of sentence (without inversion):\nSie spricht außerdem Französisch.\n\nBoth correct. Position 1 emphasizes the addition."}},
{type:"tip",title:"Paired Conjunctions: sowohl...als auch / weder...noch",text:"sowohl A als auch B = both A and B:\nSie ist sowohl intelligent als auch fleißig.\n\nweder A noch B = neither A nor B:\nEr trinkt weder Kaffee noch Tee.\n\nIMPORTANT: weder...noch is already negative.\nNever add nicht or kein on top:\nEr trinkt weder Kaffee noch Tee. (correct)\nEr trinkt nicht weder Kaffee noch Tee. (incorrect)",deepDive:{title:"weder...noch with Full Sentences",text:"With full sentences, weder triggers inversion in both parts:\nWeder hat er Zeit, noch hat er Lust.\n(Neither does he have time, nor does he feel like it.)\n\nThe verb comes in BOTH parts directly after weder/noch."}},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"struggling",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"Verumius versucht einen Satz: 'Die Karte, mit... der? die? dem? ich zum Arzt gehe...' KD hebt eine Augenbraue. 'Fast. Mit der. Die Karte ist weiblich.' Verumius seufzt. Sogar Karten haben ein Geschlecht.",src:"Verumius tries a sentence: 'The card, with... der? die? dem? I go to the doctor...' KD raises an eyebrow. 'Almost. Mit der. The card is feminine.' Verumius sighs. Even cards have a gender."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Satz hat die richtige Wortstellung?",opts:["Deshalb er geht zum Arzt.","Deshalb er zum Arzt geht.","Deshalb geht er zum Arzt.","Deshalb zum Arzt er geht."],ans:"Deshalb geht er zum Arzt.",hint:"After an adverbial conjunction, the verb comes immediately next."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die \u00c4rztin, bei {1} ich war, hat mir Tropfen verschrieben.",a:["der"],opts:["der","die","dem","den"],hint:"Bei takes dative. \u00c4rztin is feminine. What is the feminine dative relative pronoun?",sSrc:"The doctor I was at prescribed me drops."},
{type:"mc",q:"Es regnet stark. _____ bleibe ich zu Hause. Welches Wort bedeutet 'therefore'?",opts:["Deshalb","Trotzdem","Sonst","Also"],ans:"Deshalb",hint:"Which conjunction shows a direct cause-effect relationship?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Klinik, in {1} ich war, war sehr gut. {2} empfehle ich sie.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"Deshalb"},pool:["der","die","dem","Deshalb","Trotzdem","Sonst"],hint:"First blank: in + dative, feminine Klinik. Second blank: a consequence conjunction.",sSrc:"The clinic I was at was very good. Therefore I recommend it."},
{type:"story",speaker:"kd",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-ber-cafe-kd",trg:"KD klopft Verumius auf die Schulter. 'Die Grammatik, vor der du Angst hast, ist eigentlich logisch. Deshalb liebe ich Deutsch. Alles hat Regeln.' Verumius denkt: Regeln ja. Ausnahmen auch.",src:"KD pats Verumius on the shoulder. 'The grammar you are afraid of is actually logical. That is why I love German. Everything has rules.' Verumius thinks: Rules yes. Exceptions too."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 5: "Apotheke und Pflege" — Vocab + review (20 words, 24 steps)
// Pharmacy and caregiving vocabulary
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l5",title:"Apotheke und Pflege",icon:"💊",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Apotheke und Pflege",desc:"Drugstore, pharmacy, and care. Learn how to take care of sick people while practicing relative clauses and adverbial conjunctions.",goals:["Learn pharmacy and care vocabulary","Master care terminology","Practice relative clauses and adverbial conjunctions with new vocabulary"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"hapless",art:"de-ber-apotheke",trg:"Verumius steht in der Apotheke. Die Apothekerin fragt: 'Haben Sie ein Rezept?' Er zeigt ihr den Brief von der Krankenkasse. Sie lacht. 'Das ist kein Rezept. Das ist eine Mahnung.'",src:"Verumius stands in the pharmacy. The pharmacist asks: 'Do you have a prescription?' He shows her the letter from the health insurance. She laughs. 'That is not a prescription. That is a reminder notice.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Drogerie",src:"the drugstore (toiletries shop)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"NOT a drugstore in the American sense.\ndm, Rossmann, M\u00fcller: toiletries, cosmetics, household. No medicine.",example:"A: Wo kaufst du Shampoo?\nB: In der Drogerie. Bei dm oder Rossmann.\nA: Nicht in der Apotheke?\nB: Nein, die Drogerie ist f\u00fcr K\u00f6rperpflege.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do you buy shampoo?\nB: At the drugstore. At dm or Rossmann.\nA: Not at the pharmacy?\nB: No, the drugstore is for personal care.",funFact:"A famous false friend. A Drogerie sells toiletries, cosmetics, and household products. No prescription drugs. For medicine, you need the Apotheke."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zahncreme",src:"the toothpaste",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zahn (tooth) + Creme (cream).\nAlso called 'Zahnpasta.' Both are correct.",example:"A: Welche Zahncreme benutzt du?\nB: Eine mit Fluorid.\nA: Wo kaufst du sie?\nB: In der Drogerie. Die ist dort g\u00fcnstiger.",exampleSrc:"A: Which toothpaste do you use?\nB: One with fluoride.\nA: Where do you buy it?\nB: At the drugstore. It is cheaper there.",funFact:"Germans use both Zahncreme and Zahnpasta interchangeably. Regional preference: north tends toward Zahnpasta, south toward Zahncreme."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zahnpasta",src:"the toothpaste",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zahn (tooth) + Pasta (paste). From Italian.\nSynonym for Zahncreme.",example:"A: Hast du noch Zahnpasta?\nB: Nein, die ist leer.\nA: Ich kaufe neue Zahnpasta.\nB: Nimm die mit Kr\u00e4utern.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you still have toothpaste?\nB: No, it is empty.\nA: I will buy new toothpaste.\nB: Get the one with herbs.",funFact:"From Italian 'pasta' (paste). The other word for toothpaste. Both Zahncreme and Zahnpasta are correct. Regional and personal preference decides."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zahnb\u00fcrste",src:"the toothbrush",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Zahn (tooth) + B\u00fcrste (brush).\nCompound noun: you already know both halves.",example:"A: Ich brauche eine neue Zahnb\u00fcrste.\nB: Eine elektrische oder eine normale?\nA: Eine elektrische Zahnb\u00fcrste.\nB: Die kosten ab 30 Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: I need a new toothbrush.\nB: An electric one or a normal one?\nA: An electric toothbrush.\nB: Those cost from 30 euros.",funFact:"Compound noun: you already know both halves. This is how German vocabulary grows exponentially. Know the parts, know the whole."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die B\u00fcrste",src:"the brush",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Not just for teeth: Haarb\u00fcrste, Schuhb\u00fcrste, Nagelb\u00fcrste.\nA bristle tool for cleaning anything.",example:"A: Wo ist meine B\u00fcrste?\nB: Welche B\u00fcrste? Die Haarb\u00fcrste?\nA: Ja, die Haarb\u00fcrste.\nB: Im Badezimmer, neben dem Spiegel.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is my brush?\nB: Which brush? The hairbrush?\nA: Yes, the hairbrush.\nB: In the bathroom, next to the mirror.",funFact:"Haarb\u00fcrste (hairbrush), Schuhb\u00fcrste (shoe brush), Nagelb\u00fcrste (nail brush). A bristle tool for cleaning anything. From Middle High German 'burste.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Taschentuch",src:"the tissue, the handkerchief",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Tasche (pocket) + Tuch (cloth).\nTempo is the generic German word for tissue.",example:"A: Hast du ein Taschentuch?\nB: Ja, hier. Hast du Schnupfen?\nA: Ja, seit gestern.\nB: Gute Besserung!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a tissue?\nB: Yes, here. Do you have a cold?\nA: Yes, since yesterday.\nB: Get well soon!",funFact:"Tempo is the generic German word for tissue (brand name, like Kleenex in English). 'Hast du ein Taschentuch?' is what you ask when someone has Schnupfen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Pfleger",src:"the caregiver, the nurse (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'pflegen' (to care for) + -er.\n'Altenpfleger' = elderly care worker.",example:"A: Der Pfleger kommt um acht Uhr.\nB: Ist er nett?\nA: Ja, ein sehr guter Pfleger.\nB: Gut, Oma braucht gute Pflege.",exampleSrc:"A: The caregiver comes at eight o'clock.\nB: Is he nice?\nA: Yes, a very good caregiver.\nB: Good, grandma needs good care.",funFact:"An increasingly important profession in aging Germany. The country has a chronic shortage of Pfleger. 'Altenpfleger' (elderly care worker) is one of the most needed jobs."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pflegerin",src:"the caregiver, the nurse (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Pfleger + -in. Standard feminine suffix.\nThe majority of Pflege workers are female.",example:"A: Die Pflegerin ist sehr erfahren.\nB: Wie lange arbeitet sie schon?\nA: Seit zehn Jahren als Pflegerin.\nB: Das merkt man.",exampleSrc:"A: The caregiver is very experienced.\nB: How long has she been working?\nA: For ten years as a caregiver.\nB: You can tell.",funFact:"The majority of Pflege workers in Germany are female. The profession is chronically understaffed. Same pattern: male -er, female -erin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Krankenpfleger",src:"the male nurse",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Kranke (sick person) + Pfleger (carer).\nModern: 'Pflegefachkraft' for all genders.",example:"A: Mein Bruder ist Krankenpfleger.\nB: In welcher Klinik arbeitet er?\nA: In der Charit\u00e9.\nB: Das ist ein sehr guter Beruf.",exampleSrc:"A: My brother is a nurse.\nB: At which clinic does he work?\nA: At the Charit\u00e9.\nB: That is a very good profession.",funFact:"Modern German is moving toward 'Pflegefachkraft' for all genders. But 'Krankenpfleger' is still widely understood and used."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Krankenschwester",src:"the nurse (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Kranke (sick) + Schwester (sister).\nHistorically, nuns cared for the sick. The name stuck.",example:"A: Die Krankenschwester misst meinen Blutdruck.\nB: Ist er zu hoch?\nA: Nein, sagt die Krankenschwester.\nB: Gut, dann ist alles in Ordnung.",exampleSrc:"A: The nurse is measuring my blood pressure.\nB: Is it too high?\nA: No, says the nurse.\nB: Good, then everything is fine.",funFact:"Historically, nuns (Schwestern) cared for the sick. The name stuck. Being phased out officially in favor of 'Pflegefachfrau,' but still widely used."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Betreuer",src:"the supervisor, the caretaker",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'betreuen' (to look after).\nBroader than Pfleger: children, patients, elderly.",example:"A: Wer ist der Betreuer der Gruppe?\nB: Herr Schmidt. Er betreut zehn Patienten.\nA: Ist er gut?\nB: Ja, ein sehr f\u00fcrsorglicher Betreuer.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is the supervisor of the group?\nB: Mr. Schmidt. He looks after ten patients.\nA: Is he good?\nB: Yes, a very caring supervisor.",funFact:"Broader than Pfleger: a Betreuer can supervise children, patients, or elderly. 'Kinderbetreuer' (childcare worker). The person responsible for your wellbeing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Betreuerin",src:"the female supervisor, the female caretaker",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Betreuer + -in.\n'Die Betreuerin k\u00fcmmert sich um die Senioren.'",example:"A: Die Betreuerin kommt heute Nachmittag.\nB: Gut, Opa freut sich immer.\nA: Ja, die Betreuerin ist sehr nett.\nB: Er vertraut ihr.",exampleSrc:"A: The caretaker comes this afternoon.\nB: Good, grandpa always looks forward to it.\nA: Yes, the caretaker is very nice.\nB: He trusts her.",funFact:"Same pattern: male -er, female -erin. Betreuer/Betreuerin, Pfleger/Pflegerin. German is consistent with its gendered suffixes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Betreuung",src:"the care, the supervision",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'betreuen' + -ung. Abstract noun.\n'Kinderbetreuung' = childcare.",example:"A: Die Betreuung im Altenheim ist sehr gut.\nB: Wie viele Stunden am Tag?\nA: 24 Stunden Betreuung.\nB: Das ist beruhigend.",exampleSrc:"A: The care at the nursing home is very good.\nB: How many hours per day?\nA: 24-hour care.\nB: That is reassuring.",funFact:"'Kinderbetreuung' (childcare), 'Seniorenbetreuung' (elderly care). The -ung suffix creates the concept from the verb. German's favorite noun-maker."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pflegen",src:"to care for, to maintain",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Einen Kranken pflegen' = to care for a sick person.\nAlso: 'Kontakte pflegen' = to maintain contacts.",example:"A: Wer pflegt deine Mutter?\nB: Ein Pfleger kommt jeden Tag.\nA: Pflegt er sie gut?\nB: Ja, er pflegt sie mit viel Geduld.",exampleSrc:"A: Who cares for your mother?\nB: A caregiver comes every day.\nA: Does he care for her well?\nB: Yes, he cares for her with great patience.",funFact:"Care in every sense. 'Einen Kranken pflegen' (to care for a sick person). 'Kontakte pflegen' (to maintain contacts). 'Den Garten pflegen' (to tend the garden)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"betreuen",src:"to look after, to supervise",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable prefix be-.\nBroader than pflegen. 'Kinder betreuen' = to look after children.",example:"A: Wer betreut die Kinder?\nB: Eine Betreuerin betreut sie.\nA: Wie viele Kinder betreut sie?\nB: Zehn Kinder pro Gruppe.",exampleSrc:"A: Who looks after the children?\nB: A caretaker looks after them.\nA: How many children does she look after?\nB: Ten children per group.",funFact:"Be- + treuen (loyalty-related root). To be loyal to someone by watching over them. Inseparable prefix. Broader than pflegen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erleichtern",src:"to ease, to relieve",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Er- + leicht (light/easy) + -ern. To make lighter.\n'Erleichtert sein' = to be relieved.",example:"A: Diese Medizin erleichtert den Schmerz.\nB: Wirklich? Wie schnell?\nA: Nach etwa 30 Minuten.\nB: Gut, ich bin erleichtert.",exampleSrc:"A: This medicine eases the pain.\nB: Really? How fast?\nA: After about 30 minutes.\nB: Good, I am relieved.",funFact:"A beautiful compound verb. Er- + leicht (light/easy) + -ern. To make lighter. Recovery is literally making the burden lighter."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verbinden",src:"to bandage, to connect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + binden (to bind).\n'Eine Wunde verbinden' = to bandage a wound.",example:"A: Ich muss die Wunde verbinden.\nB: Haben Sie einen Verband?\nA: Ja, ich verbinde das sofort.\nB: Danke, das tut schon besser.",exampleSrc:"A: I need to bandage the wound.\nB: Do you have a bandage?\nA: Yes, I will bandage it right away.\nB: Thanks, that feels better already.",funFact:"The bandage binds; the phone line connects. Same verb. 'Eine Wunde verbinden' (to bandage a wound). 'Verbunden sein' (to be connected)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ersetzen",src:"to replace",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Er- + setzen (to set/place).\nTo set something new in the place of the old.",example:"A: Wir m\u00fcssen das Pflaster ersetzen.\nB: Wie oft?\nA: Jeden Tag ersetzen.\nB: Und dann heilt die Wunde schneller?",exampleSrc:"A: We need to replace the bandage.\nB: How often?\nA: Replace it every day.\nB: And then the wound heals faster?",funFact:"'Nichts kann Gesundheit ersetzen' (Nothing can replace health). To set something new in the place of the old. The verb that built the Ersatz noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Ersatz",src:"the replacement, the substitute",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From ersetzen. 'Ersatzteil' = spare part.\nEntered English during the World Wars.",example:"A: Haben Sie einen Ersatz f\u00fcr dieses Medikament?\nB: Ja, es gibt einen g\u00fcnstigen Ersatz.\nA: Wirkt der Ersatz genauso gut?\nB: Ja, gleicher Wirkstoff.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a substitute for this medicine?\nB: Yes, there is a cheaper substitute.\nA: Does the substitute work just as well?\nB: Yes, same active ingredient.",funFact:"During both World Wars, 'Ersatz' entered English as a word meaning cheap substitute. Germans use it neutrally. 'Ersatzteil' (spare part). 'Kaffee-Ersatz' (coffee substitute)."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-apotheke",trg:"Die Apothekerin gibt Verumius eine T\u00fcte mit Nasentropfen, Hustensaft und Pflastern. 'Gute Besserung,' sagt sie. Er l\u00e4chelt. Das ist die erste deutsche Redewendung, die er ohne Nachdenken versteht.",src:"The pharmacist hands Verumius a bag with nose drops, cough syrup, and bandages. 'Get well soon,' she says. He smiles. That is the first German expression he understands without thinking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Besserung",src:"the improvement, the recovery",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'besser' (better) + -ung.\n'Gute Besserung!' = Get well soon!",example:"A: Gute Besserung!\nB: Danke! Ich hoffe auf schnelle Besserung.\nA: Ruh dich gut aus.\nB: Mache ich. Danke f\u00fcr die Genesungsw\u00fcnsche.",exampleSrc:"A: Get well soon!\nB: Thanks! I hope for a quick recovery.\nA: Rest well.\nB: I will. Thanks for the well wishes.",funFact:"'Gute Besserung!' is THE thing Germans say when someone is sick. The most important two-word phrase in German healthcare culture. Say it often."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du brauchst Shampoo und Zahnpasta. Wohin gehst du?",opts:["Drogerie","Apotheke","Klinik","Notaufnahme"],ans:"Drogerie",hint:"This store sells toiletries and cosmetics, not prescription medicine."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Pflegerin arbeitet hart. {1} ist sie oft ersch\u00f6pft.",a:["Deshalb"],opts:["Deshalb","Trotzdem","Weil","Dass"],hint:"Which word means 'therefore' and is followed by verb-second word order?",sSrc:"The nurse works hard. Therefore she is often exhausted."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Die Salbe, {1} der Arzt mir verschrieben hat, hilft nicht. {2} brauche ich ein anderes Schmerzmittel.",blanks:{"1":"die","2":"Deswegen"},pool:["die","der","das","Deswegen","Trotzdem","Weil"],hint:"First blank: accusative relative pronoun for feminine Salbe. Second blank: consequence conjunction + verb-second.",sSrc:"The ointment the doctor prescribed me does not help. That is why I need a different painkiller."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"relieved",art:"de-ber-apotheke",trg:"Verumius verl\u00e4sst die Apotheke mit drei T\u00fcten und einer Versichertenkarte, die er jetzt tats\u00e4chlich benutzen kann. Das System funktioniert. Trotzdem versteht er die Beipackzettel nicht. Schritt f\u00fcr Schritt.",src:"Verumius leaves the pharmacy with three bags and an insurance card he can actually use now. The system works. Nevertheless, he does not understand the package inserts. Step by step."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 6: "TK oder AOK?" — Story climax (18 words, 22 steps)
// Scene 3: The decision
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l6",title:"TK oder AOK?",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"TK oder AOK?",desc:"Verumius makes his decision. Two brochures, one pen, one moment. Learn pension and social system vocabulary.",goals:["Learn pension and social system vocabulary","Follow Verumius through his first adult decision in German","Combine relative clauses with adverbial conjunctions"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-kitchen-clean",trg:"Der K\u00fcchentisch ist aufger\u00e4umt. Zwanzig Briefe sind jetzt zwei Brosch\u00fcren. Verumius h\u00e4lt einen Stift in der Hand. Die Versicherung, f\u00fcr die er sich entscheidet, wird ihn die n\u00e4chsten Jahre begleiten.",src:"The kitchen table is tidy. Twenty letters are now two brochures. Verumius holds a pen in his hand. The insurance he chooses will accompany him for the next years."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Rente",src:"the pension, the retirement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"'In Rente gehen' = to retire. From Latin 'renta.'\nRentenversicherung (pension insurance) is mandatory.",example:"A: Wann gehst du in Rente?\nB: Mit 67. Noch 30 Jahre.\nA: Bekommst du eine gute Rente?\nB: Ich hoffe es. Ich zahle jeden Monat ein.",exampleSrc:"A: When will you retire?\nB: At 67. Another 30 years.\nA: Will you get a good pension?\nB: I hope so. I pay in every month.",funFact:"The German Rentensystem is pay-as-you-go: today's workers fund today's retirees. 'Rentenversicherung' (pension insurance) is mandatory for all employees."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pension",src:"the pension (civil servants), the guesthouse",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Two meanings: retirement pay for Beamte, or a small hotel.\nContext is essential.",example:"A: Mein Vater bekommt eine Pension.\nB: Ist er Beamter?\nA: Ja, er war 40 Jahre Lehrer.\nB: Dann ist die Pension sicher gut.",exampleSrc:"A: My father gets a pension.\nB: Is he a civil servant?\nA: Yes, he was a teacher for 40 years.\nB: Then the pension is surely good.",funFact:"Two meanings. For civil servants: retirement pay (Beamtenpension). For travelers: a small guesthouse. 'In Pension gehen' (to retire, for Beamte). Context is essential."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Senior",src:"the senior, the elderly person",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'senior' (older).\n'Seniorenrabatt' = senior discount.",example:"A: Gibt es einen Seniorenrabatt?\nB: Ja, f\u00fcr Senioren ab 65 Jahren.\nA: Wie viel Prozent?\nB: 20 Prozent auf alle Eintrittskarten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a senior discount?\nB: Yes, for seniors from 65 years.\nA: How many percent?\nB: 20 percent on all tickets.",funFact:"'Seniorenrabatt' (senior discount), 'Seniorenticket' (reduced fare). Respectful term for older adults. From Latin 'senior' (older)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Seniorin",src:"the senior (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Senior + -in. Standard feminine formation.\nGerman insists on gendered forms, even for international words.",example:"A: Die Seniorin joggt jeden Morgen.\nB: Wie alt ist sie?\nA: 78 Jahre alt.\nB: Beeindruckend! Eine sportliche Seniorin.",exampleSrc:"A: The senior woman jogs every morning.\nB: How old is she?\nA: 78 years old.\nB: Impressive! An athletic senior.",funFact:"German insists on gendered forms, even for international words. Senior becomes Seniorin. The -in suffix is universal for person nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Pensionist",src:"the pensioner, the retiree",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Austrian German primarily.\nIn Germany, 'Rentner' is more common.",example:"A: Mein Nachbar ist Pensionist.\nB: Aus \u00d6sterreich?\nA: Ja, er ist aus Wien.\nB: Dort sagt man Pensionist statt Rentner.",exampleSrc:"A: My neighbor is a pensioner.\nB: From Austria?\nA: Yes, he is from Vienna.\nB: There they say Pensionist instead of Rentner.",funFact:"Austrian German primarily. In Germany, 'Rentner' is more common. Regional variation within German-speaking countries shows the language is not monolithic."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Pensionistin",src:"the pensioner (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Austrian form. Pensionist + -in.\nStandard feminine formation.",example:"A: Die Pensionistin lebt in Salzburg.\nB: Bekommt sie eine gute Pension?\nA: Ja, sie war Lehrerin.\nB: Lehrerinnen bekommen gute Pensionen.",exampleSrc:"A: The pensioner lives in Salzburg.\nB: Does she get a good pension?\nA: Yes, she was a teacher.\nB: Teachers get good pensions.",funFact:"Austrian form. Four morphemes: Pension-ist-in. Standard feminine formation applied to a regional word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Altenheim",src:"the nursing home",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Alten (old people) + Heim (home).\nGermany has over 15,000 Altenheime.",example:"A: Meine Oma wohnt im Altenheim.\nB: Gef\u00e4llt es ihr dort?\nA: Ja, das Altenheim ist sehr sch\u00f6n.\nB: Hat sie gute Betreuung?",exampleSrc:"A: My grandma lives in the nursing home.\nB: Does she like it there?\nA: Yes, the nursing home is very nice.\nB: Does she have good care?",funFact:"A place where Senioren receive Betreuung and Pflege. Germany has over 15,000 Altenheime. The aging population makes this an increasingly important topic."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Altersheim",src:"the retirement home",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Alter (age) + Heim (home). Synonym for Altenheim.\nRegional preference decides which one you hear.",example:"A: Gibt es ein Altersheim in der N\u00e4he?\nB: Ja, am Stadtrand.\nA: Ist das Altersheim gut?\nB: Ja, es hat einen guten Ruf.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a retirement home nearby?\nB: Yes, on the outskirts.\nA: Is the retirement home good?\nB: Yes, it has a good reputation.",funFact:"'Altersheim' focuses on age; 'Altenheim' focuses on the people. Both mean the same thing. Regional preference decides which one you hear."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"overwhelmed",art:"de-ber-kitchen-clean",trg:"TK: g\u00fcnstig, gute App, moderner Service. AOK: \u00e4lteste Kasse, mehr Filialen, pers\u00f6nliche Beratung. Verumius starrt auf die zwei Brosch\u00fcren. Die Entscheidung, f\u00fcr die er sich treffen muss, f\u00fchlt sich endg\u00fcltig an.",src:"TK: affordable, good app, modern service. AOK: oldest fund, more branches, personal advice. Verumius stares at the two brochures. The decision he has to make feels final."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einrichtung",src:"the facility, the institution",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ein (in) + Richtung (direction) = arrangement.\nAlso means furniture ('die Einrichtung des Zimmers').",example:"A: Die Einrichtung ist modern.\nB: Welche Einrichtung meinst du?\nA: Die medizinische Einrichtung am Park.\nB: Ah ja, die ist erst letztes Jahr er\u00f6ffnet worden.",exampleSrc:"A: The facility is modern.\nB: Which facility do you mean?\nA: The medical facility by the park.\nB: Ah yes, that one only opened last year.",funFact:"To set things in the right direction. 'Eine medizinische Einrichtung' (a medical facility). Also: furniture ('die Einrichtung des Zimmers'). Direction and arrangement in one word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"pensionieren",src:"to pension off, to retire",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"The -ieren ending makes it regular.\nPrimarily for Beamte. Workers: 'in Rente gehen.'",example:"A: Wann wird er pensioniert?\nB: N\u00e4chstes Jahr.\nA: Freut er sich?\nB: Ja, er wurde letzten Monat informiert.",exampleSrc:"A: When will he be retired?\nB: Next year.\nA: Is he looking forward to it?\nB: Yes, he was informed last month.",funFact:"Primarily for civil servants (Beamte). For normal workers: 'in Rente gehen.' Germany has two retirement systems: one for Beamte, one for everyone else."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Not",src:"the need, the distress, the emergency",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Root of Notfall, Notaufnahme, Notruf, Notausgang.\nOne tiny word spawns an entire emergency vocabulary.",example:"A: Er ist in gro\u00dfer Not.\nB: Was ist passiert?\nA: Er hat sein Geld verloren.\nB: Wir m\u00fcssen ihm helfen.",exampleSrc:"A: He is in great distress.\nB: What happened?\nA: He lost his money.\nB: We need to help him.",funFact:"Root of Notfall, Notaufnahme, Notruf, Notausgang. One tiny word spawns an entire emergency vocabulary. 'Not macht erfinderisch' (Necessity is the mother of invention)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Notausgang",src:"the emergency exit",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Not (emergency) + Ausgang (exit).\nGreen signs, required by law in every public building.",example:"A: Wo ist der Notausgang?\nB: Dort hinten, neben der Treppe.\nA: Danke. Man sollte immer wissen, wo er ist.\nB: Genau, das ist Sicherheit.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the emergency exit?\nB: Back there, next to the stairs.\nA: Thanks. You should always know where it is.\nB: Exactly, that is safety.",funFact:"Green signs with a running figure. Required by law in every public building. 'Wo ist der Notausgang?' is essential survival German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Opfer",src:"the victim, the sacrifice",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'offerre' (to offer).\nBoth meanings: the one harmed and the one given up.",example:"A: Wie viele Opfer gab es?\nB: Drei Verletzte, keine Toten.\nA: Das ist schrecklich.\nB: Ja, die Opfer werden im Krankenhaus behandelt.",exampleSrc:"A: How many victims were there?\nB: Three injured, no dead.\nA: That is terrible.\nB: Yes, the victims are being treated in the hospital.",funFact:"The word holds both meanings: the one harmed and the one given up. 'Unfallopfer' (accident victim). 'Ein Opfer bringen' (to make a sacrifice). Same word, dual fate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Tod",src:"death",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine despite being abstract.\nCognate with English 'death.' Often personified.",example:"A: Der Tod ist ein schwieriges Thema.\nB: Ja, aber ein wichtiges.\nA: In Deutschland spricht man offen dar\u00fcber.\nB: Das finde ich gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Death is a difficult topic.\nB: Yes, but an important one.\nA: In Germany, people talk about it openly.\nB: I think that is good.",funFact:"Often personified in German literature as 'der Sensenmann' (the grim reaper). Cognate with English 'death.' Masculine, despite being an abstract noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Tote",src:"the dead person (female), the dead",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Adjectival noun from 'tot' (dead).\nDer/die Tote changes with gender and case like an adjective.",example:"A: Die Polizei fand eine Tote.\nB: Wer war die Tote?\nA: Das wird noch ermittelt.\nB: Die Zahl der Toten steigt.",exampleSrc:"A: The police found a dead woman.\nB: Who was the dead woman?\nA: That is still being investigated.\nB: The number of dead is rising.",funFact:"Adjectival noun: der/die Tote changes with gender and case like an adjective. 'Die Zahl der Toten' (the number of dead). Grammatically, death is declined."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kranke",src:"the sick person (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Adjectival noun from 'krank.'\nDer Kranke (male), die Kranke (female).",example:"A: Die Kranke braucht Ruhe.\nB: Wie geht es der Kranken?\nA: Besser. Die Kranke erholt sich langsam.\nB: Das sind gute Nachrichten.",exampleSrc:"A: The sick woman needs rest.\nB: How is the sick woman doing?\nA: Better. The sick woman is recovering slowly.\nB: That is good news.",funFact:"Another adjective acting as a noun. Der Kranke (male), die Kranke (female). 'Die Kranken pflegen' (to care for the sick). Adjective becomes person."},
{type:"teach",trg:"t\u00f6dlich",src:"deadly, fatal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Tod + -lich.\n'T\u00f6dlich langweilig' = deadly boring (emphasis).",example:"A: Ist die Krankheit t\u00f6dlich?\nB: Nein, nicht mit der richtigen Behandlung.\nA: Gott sei Dank.\nB: Aber ohne Behandlung kann sie t\u00f6dlich sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the disease deadly?\nB: No, not with the right treatment.\nA: Thank God.\nB: But without treatment it can be deadly.",funFact:"Germans use t\u00f6dlich for emphasis, like English 'dead tired.' 'T\u00f6dlich langweilig' (deadly boring). From Tod + -lich. The adjective of death."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"comedic-tension",art:"de-ber-kitchen-clean",trg:"Verumius nimmt den Stift. Legt ihn wieder hin. Nimmt ihn wieder. Lukas schreibt eine Nachricht: 'Nimm einfach TK. Die haben eine App.' Verumius denkt: So trifft man also erwachsene Entscheidungen in Deutschland.",src:"Verumius picks up the pen. Puts it down. Picks it up again. Lukas texts: 'Just take TK. They have an app.' Verumius thinks: So this is how you make adult decisions in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Lieferung",src:"the delivery",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'liefern' (to deliver) + -ung.\nIn insurance: what the Krankenkasse delivers (pays for).",example:"A: Wann kommt die Lieferung?\nB: Die Lieferung kommt morgen.\nA: Gut, ich warte auf die Medikamentenlieferung.\nB: Sie wird bis 12 Uhr geliefert.",exampleSrc:"A: When does the delivery come?\nB: The delivery comes tomorrow.\nA: Good, I am waiting for the medicine delivery.\nB: It will be delivered by 12 o'clock.",funFact:"In the insurance context: what the Krankenkasse delivers (pays for). 'Medikamentenlieferung' (medicine delivery). From 'liefern' (to deliver) + -ung."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"triumphant",art:"de-ber-kitchen-clean",trg:"Verumius kreist 'TK' ein. Die Entscheidung, \u00fcber die er zwei Wochen nachgedacht hat, ist getroffen. Trotzdem f\u00fchlt er sich erleichtert. Also ist er jetzt ein richtiger Berliner.",src:"Verumius circles 'TK.' The decision he thought about for two weeks is made. Nevertheless, he feels relieved. So he is now a real Berliner."},
{type:"mc",q:"Die Versicherung, _____ ich mich entschieden habe, ist die TK. Was passt?",opts:["f\u00fcr der","f\u00fcr die","f\u00fcr das","f\u00fcr den"],ans:"f\u00fcr die",hint:"sich entscheiden f\u00fcr + accusative. Versicherung is feminine."},

{type:"fb",s:"Jeder Arbeitnehmer muss monatlich in die Rentenversicherung {1}.",a:["einzahlen"],opts:["einzahlen","abmelden","verwalten","\u00fcbertragen"],hint:"The separable verb for making regular contributions to a pension or insurance fund.",sSrc:"Every employee must pay into the pension insurance monthly."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 7: "Pr\u00fcfung: Gesundheit und System" — Comprehensive quiz (15 words, 22 steps)
// Assessment of both grammar constructs
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l7",title:"Pr\u00fcfung: Gesundheit und System",icon:"📝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Pr\u00fcfung: Gesundheit und System",desc:"Test your knowledge of health and insurance vocabulary. Show that you have mastered relative clauses and adverbial conjunctions.",goals:["Test health and insurance vocabulary","Prove mastery of relative clauses with prepositions","Show competence with adverbial conjunctions"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"montage",art:"de-ber-kitchen-study",trg:"Verumius sitzt mit Karteikarten am K\u00fcchentisch. Auf jeder Karte steht ein Wort: Versicherung, Notaufnahme, Zuzahlung. Diesmal liegt kein Chaos vor ihm. Nur Wissen.",src:"Verumius sits at the kitchen table with flashcards. On each card is a word: insurance, emergency room, co-payment. This time there is no chaos in front of him. Only knowledge."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Raucher",src:"the smoker (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'rauchen' (to smoke) + -er.\n'Raucherbereich' = smoking area.",example:"A: Bist du Raucher?\nB: Nein, ich habe vor drei Jahren aufgeh\u00f6rt.\nA: Gut gemacht! Rauchen ist ungesund.\nB: Ja, ich f\u00fchle mich viel besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you a smoker?\nB: No, I quit three years ago.\nA: Well done! Smoking is unhealthy.\nB: Yes, I feel much better.",funFact:"Germany was one of the last EU countries to ban indoor smoking (2007). 'Raucher oder Nichtraucher?' was once asked on every train."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Raucherin",src:"the smoker (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Raucher + -in. Standard feminine suffix.\nSame pattern as Pfleger/Pflegerin.",example:"A: Ist sie Raucherin?\nB: Ja, leider. Sie raucht seit 20 Jahren.\nA: Das ist schlecht f\u00fcr die Gesundheit.\nB: Ich wei\u00df, aber sie kann nicht aufh\u00f6ren.",exampleSrc:"A: Is she a smoker?\nB: Yes, unfortunately. She has been smoking for 20 years.\nA: That is bad for health.\nB: I know, but she cannot quit.",funFact:"Same pattern as Pfleger/Pflegerin, Betreuer/Betreuerin. German's consistent feminine suffix at work."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Nichtraucher",src:"the non-smoker (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Nicht + Raucher. The Nicht- prefix negates.\n'Nichtraucherzone' = non-smoking zone.",example:"A: Ich bin Nichtraucher.\nB: Sehr gut. Seit immer?\nA: Ja, ich habe nie geraucht.\nB: Beneidenswert!",exampleSrc:"A: I am a non-smoker.\nB: Very good. Since always?\nA: Yes, I have never smoked.\nB: Enviable!",funFact:"The Nicht- prefix negates the person noun. 'Nichtraucher sein' (to be a non-smoker) is now the default in public spaces across Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Nichtraucherin",src:"the non-smoker (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Nichtraucher + -in.\nFour morphemes: Nicht-rauch-er-in.",example:"A: Sie ist \u00fcberzeugte Nichtraucherin.\nB: Gut f\u00fcr sie.\nA: Ja, sie hat nie angefangen.\nB: Das ist die beste Entscheidung.",exampleSrc:"A: She is a committed non-smoker.\nB: Good for her.\nA: Yes, she never started.\nB: That is the best decision.",funFact:"Four morphemes in one word: Nicht-rauch-er-in. German stacks prefixes and suffixes like building blocks. Know the parts, decode any word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sucht",src:"the addiction",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From 'suchen' (to seek). An endless seeking.\n'Drogensucht' = drug addiction.",example:"A: Sucht ist eine Krankheit.\nB: Ja, eine sehr ernste.\nA: Kann man Sucht heilen?\nB: Mit Therapie und Unterst\u00fctzung, ja.",exampleSrc:"A: Addiction is a disease.\nB: Yes, a very serious one.\nA: Can you cure addiction?\nB: With therapy and support, yes.",funFact:"From 'suchen' (to seek). An addiction is an endless seeking. 'Drogensucht' (drug addiction), 'Spielsucht' (gambling addiction), 'Internetsucht' (internet addiction). Whatever you cannot stop seeking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Suchtmittel",src:"the addictive substance",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Sucht (addiction) + Mittel (substance/means).\nClinical, official, legal.",example:"A: Alkohol ist ein Suchtmittel.\nB: Ja, und Nikotin auch.\nA: Welche Suchtmittel sind legal?\nB: Alkohol, Nikotin und Koffein.",exampleSrc:"A: Alcohol is an addictive substance.\nB: Yes, and nicotine too.\nA: Which addictive substances are legal?\nB: Alcohol, nicotine, and caffeine.",funFact:"The compound is clinical, official, legal. Used in medical and legal contexts. 'Suchtmittelgesetz' (narcotics law). German compounds leave nothing ambiguous."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Droge",src:"the drug",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Dutch 'droog' (dry). Originally dried herbs.\nThe Drogerie kept the old, innocent meaning.",example:"A: Drogen sind gef\u00e4hrlich.\nB: Ja, besonders harte Drogen.\nA: Gibt es Hilfe f\u00fcr Abh\u00e4ngige?\nB: Ja, es gibt Drogenberatungsstellen.",exampleSrc:"A: Drugs are dangerous.\nB: Yes, especially hard drugs.\nA: Is there help for addicts?\nB: Yes, there are drug counseling centers.",funFact:"From Dutch 'droog' (dry). Originally meant dried herbs and spices. The meaning shifted to illegal substances. The Drogerie kept the old, innocent meaning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Gift",src:"poison",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"The ultimate false friend.\nEnglish 'gift' = present. German 'Gift' = poison.",example:"A: Vorsicht, das ist Gift!\nB: Wirklich? Es sieht harmlos aus.\nA: Nein, das ist sehr giftiges Material.\nB: Danke f\u00fcr die Warnung!",exampleSrc:"A: Careful, that is poison!\nB: Really? It looks harmless.\nA: No, that is very poisonous material.\nB: Thanks for the warning!",funFact:"The ultimate false friend. English 'gift' = present. German 'Gift' = poison. Same root (something given), opposite outcomes. Do not confuse at the pharmacy."},
{type:"teach",trg:"s\u00fcchtig",src:"addicted",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Sucht + -ig.\n'S\u00fcchtig machen' = to be addictive. Can be serious or playful.",example:"A: Bist du s\u00fcchtig nach Kaffee?\nB: Ja, total s\u00fcchtig! Drei Tassen am Tag.\nA: Das ist noch nicht schlimm.\nB: Aber ohne Kaffee bin ich nicht funktionsf\u00e4hig.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you addicted to coffee?\nB: Yes, totally addicted! Three cups a day.\nA: That is not so bad yet.\nB: But without coffee I cannot function.",funFact:"Can be serious or playful. 'S\u00fcchtig nach Schokolade' (addicted to chocolate) is lighthearted. 'Drogenabh\u00e4ngig' is the clinical term for serious addiction."},
{type:"teach",trg:"blind",src:"blind",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Same in English and German.\n'Blinder Passagier' = stowaway (blind passenger).",example:"A: Mein Opa ist fast blind.\nB: Braucht er Hilfe im Alltag?\nA: Ja, ein Betreuer kommt t\u00e4glich.\nB: Gut, dass er Unterst\u00fctzung hat.",exampleSrc:"A: My grandpa is almost blind.\nB: Does he need help in daily life?\nA: Yes, a caregiver comes daily.\nB: Good that he has support.",funFact:"From Proto-Germanic *blindaz. 'Blinder Passagier' (stowaway, literally 'blind passenger'). 'Blindenschrift' = Braille (blind-writing)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"taub",src:"deaf, numb",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Cognate with English 'deaf' through sound shifts.\nAlso means 'numb': 'Mein Finger ist taub.'",example:"A: Sie ist seit der Kindheit taub.\nB: Kann sie Geb\u00e4rdensprache?\nA: Ja, flie\u00dfend.\nB: Beeindruckend.",exampleSrc:"A: She has been deaf since childhood.\nB: Can she do sign language?\nA: Yes, fluently.\nB: Impressive.",funFact:"Also means 'numb.' 'Mein Finger ist taub' (My finger is numb). 'Geh\u00f6rlos' (hearing-less) is preferred in modern usage over 'taubstumm' (deaf-mute)."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"proud",art:"de-ber-kitchen-study",trg:"Verumius dreht eine Karteikarte um. 'Gift: Poison, nicht Present.' Er grinst. Vor drei Wochen h\u00e4tte er das verwechselt. Trotzdem bleibt er vorsichtig. Beamtendeutsch ist immer eine Falle.",src:"Verumius turns over a flashcard. 'Gift: Poison, not present.' He grins. Three weeks ago he would have confused that. Nevertheless, he stays careful. Bureaucratic German is always a trap."},
{type:"teach",trg:"link",src:"left (direction), sneaky",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"'Die linke Hand' = the left hand.\nColloquially: 'ein linker Typ' = a shady character.",example:"A: Bist du Linksh\u00e4nder?\nB: Ja, ich schreibe mit der linken Hand.\nA: Interessant. Mein Bruder auch.\nB: Wir sind etwa zehn Prozent der Bev\u00f6lkerung.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you left-handed?\nB: Yes, I write with the left hand.\nA: Interesting. My brother too.\nB: We are about ten percent of the population.",funFact:"The association of left with dishonesty exists in many languages (Latin 'sinister'). Colloquially: 'ein linker Typ' (a shady character). An ancient bias preserved in language."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-kitchen-study",trg:"Von Versicherung bis Sucht, von Pflaster bis Gift. Verumius hat in drei Wochen mehr \u00fcber das deutsche Gesundheitssystem gelernt als \u00fcber r\u00f6mische Medizin in f\u00fcnf Jahren Studium.",src:"From insurance to addiction, from bandages to poison. Verumius has learned more about the German healthcare system in three weeks than about Roman medicine in five years of study."},
{type:"teach",trg:"stechen",src:"to sting, to stab, to prick",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: sticht, stach, gestochen.\nRelated to English 'stick.'",example:"A: Au! Die Biene hat mich gestochen!\nB: Wo hat sie dich gestochen?\nA: Am Arm. Es brennt und sticht.\nB: Lass mich sehen. Bist du allergisch?",exampleSrc:"A: Ow! The bee stung me!\nB: Where did it sting you?\nA: On the arm. It burns and stings.\nB: Let me see. Are you allergic?",funFact:"'Die Biene sticht' (The bee stings). 'Es sticht in der Brust' (There is a stabbing pain in the chest). Related to English 'stick.' Irregular: sticht, stach, gestochen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schieben",src:"to push, to shove",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: schob, geschoben.\n'Den Rollstuhl schieben' = to push the wheelchair.",example:"A: Kannst du den Rollstuhl schieben?\nB: Ja, kein Problem.\nA: Vorsichtig, die Rampe ist steil.\nB: Ich schiebe ganz langsam.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you push the wheelchair?\nB: Yes, no problem.\nA: Carefully, the ramp is steep.\nB: I will push very slowly.",funFact:"'Etwas auf die lange Bank schieben' (to put something on the long bench) = to procrastinate. Irregular: schob, geschoben. Pushing in every sense."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wiegen",src:"to weigh",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Irregular: wog, gewogen.\nAlso: 'das Baby wiegen' = to rock the baby.",example:"A: Wie viel wiegen Sie?\nB: Etwa 80 Kilo.\nA: Das ist ein normales Gewicht.\nB: Ja, ich achte auf meine Gesundheit.",exampleSrc:"A: How much do you weigh?\nB: About 80 kilos.\nA: That is a normal weight.\nB: Yes, I pay attention to my health.",funFact:"Two different verbs that merged into one form. 'Wie viel wiegen Sie?' (How much do you weigh?). 'Das Baby wiegen' (to rock the baby). Context decides."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du siehst ein Etikett mit 'Gift' auf einer Flasche in der Apotheke. Was bedeutet es?",opts:["Poison","Present","Medicine","Supplement"],ans:"Poison",hint:"This is the most famous German-English false friend. Not a present!"},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Apotheke, {1} der ich meine Medizin hole, ist in der N\u00e4he.",a:["bei"],opts:["bei","mit","f\u00fcr","\u00fcber"],hint:"Which preposition means 'at' or 'from' when collecting something from a place?",sSrc:"The pharmacy I get my medicine from is nearby."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Der Patient, {1} dem die \u00c4rztin die Spritze gegeben hat, hatte Angst. {2} war er danach erleichtert.",blanks:{"1":"dem","2":"Trotzdem"},pool:["dem","den","der","Trotzdem","Deshalb","Sonst"],hint:"First blank: dative masculine relative pronoun. Second blank: contrast conjunction (despite that).",sSrc:"The patient the doctor gave the injection to was afraid. Nevertheless, he was relieved afterwards."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du hast Fieber. _____ solltest du zum Arzt gehen. Welches Wort bedeutet 'that is why'?",opts:["Trotzdem","Deswegen","Sonst","Also"],ans:"Deswegen",hint:"This conjunction shows direct consequence, similar to 'deshalb.'"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Sucht",src:"addiction"},{trg:"Gift",src:"poison"},{trg:"Droge",src:"drug"},{trg:"Pflaster",src:"bandage"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Nimm deine Medizin. {1} wird es schlimmer.",a:["Sonst"],opts:["Sonst","Deshalb","Trotzdem","Also"],hint:"Which conjunction means 'otherwise' and warns of a negative consequence?",sSrc:"Take your medicine. Otherwise it will get worse."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"confident",art:"de-ber-kitchen-study",trg:"Verumius legt die letzte Karteikarte weg. Die Pr\u00fcfung, vor der er Angst hatte, war gar nicht so schlimm. Also kann er vielleicht doch Beamtendeutsch. Ein bisschen.",src:"Verumius puts down the last flashcard. The exam he was afraid of was not so bad after all. So maybe he can handle bureaucratic German. A little."}
]},

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Lesson 8: "Hildis Servietten-Diagramm" — Resolution + culture (18 words, 23 steps)
// Scene 4: Hildi explains the system
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
{id:"deu_r20l8",title:"Hildis Servietten-Diagramm",icon:"📝",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Hildis Servietten-Diagramm",desc:"Hildi draws the German health system on a napkin. It is surprisingly clear. Learn the final vocabulary and review all grammar.",goals:["Learn the final unit vocabulary","Understand the German health system through Hildi's explanation","Review relative clauses and adverbial conjunctions"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"teaching",art:"de-ber-hildi-kitchen",trg:"Also, pass auf. Die Krankenkasse, bei der du versichert bist, ist die TK. Deshalb bekommst du eine Versichertenkarte. Damit gehst du zum Arzt.",src:"Alright, pay attention. The health insurance fund you are insured with is TK. Therefore you get an insurance card. You take that to the doctor."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die M\u00fcnze",src:"the coin",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'moneta' (mint).\nRelated to English 'money' and 'mint.'",example:"A: Hast du eine M\u00fcnze f\u00fcr den Automaten?\nB: Ja, hier ist eine 1-Euro-M\u00fcnze.\nA: Danke! Der Automat nimmt nur M\u00fcnzen.\nB: Kein Schein? Nur M\u00fcnzen?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a coin for the machine?\nB: Yes, here is a 1-euro coin.\nA: Thanks! The machine only takes coins.\nB: No bills? Only coins?",funFact:"German parking meters still love M\u00fcnzen. The 1-Euro-M\u00fcnze has country-specific designs on the back. Each country's coin tells a different story."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abheben",src:"to withdraw (money), to lift off",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable: 'Geld abheben' = to withdraw money.\nAlso: 'Das Flugzeug hebt ab' = the plane lifts off.",example:"A: Ich muss Geld abheben.\nB: Wo ist der n\u00e4chste Geldautomat?\nA: Um die Ecke. Ich hebe schnell 100 Euro ab.\nB: Gut, ich warte hier.",exampleSrc:"A: I need to withdraw money.\nB: Where is the nearest ATM?\nA: Around the corner. I will quickly withdraw 100 euros.\nB: Good, I will wait here.",funFact:"Money leaves the account; the plane leaves the ground. Same verb. Separable: 'Ich hebe 100 Euro ab.' The ab- prefix means away/off."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abnehmen",src:"to lose weight, to decrease, to pick up (phone)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable: ab- (off/down) + nehmen (to take).\nThree meanings, all about taking something away.",example:"A: Ich m\u00f6chte f\u00fcnf Kilo abnehmen.\nB: Dann musst du weniger essen.\nA: Oder mehr Sport machen.\nB: Am besten beides!",exampleSrc:"A: I would like to lose five kilos.\nB: Then you need to eat less.\nA: Or exercise more.\nB: Best to do both!",funFact:"Three meanings, all about taking something away. 'F\u00fcnf Kilo abnehmen' (to lose five kilos). 'Den H\u00f6rer abnehmen' (to pick up the receiver). 'Die Kosten nehmen ab' (Costs are decreasing)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zunehmen",src:"to gain weight, to increase",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"The opposite of abnehmen.\nZu- (to/toward) + nehmen = to take on more.",example:"A: Im Winter nehme ich immer zu.\nB: Wie viel?\nA: Etwa zwei Kilo.\nB: Das ist nicht viel. Im Fr\u00fchling nimmst du wieder ab.",exampleSrc:"A: In winter I always gain weight.\nB: How much?\nA: About two kilos.\nB: That is not much. In spring you will lose it again.",funFact:"What goes up (zunehmen) can come down (abnehmen). 'Die Kosten nehmen zu' (Costs are increasing). The opposite twins of German weight and finance talk."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich erk\u00e4lten",src:"to catch a cold",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive. Er- + kalt = to become cold.\nPerfekt: 'Ich habe mich erk\u00e4ltet.'",example:"A: Ich habe mich erk\u00e4ltet.\nB: Schon wieder? Zieh dich w\u00e4rmer an.\nA: Ja, es war zu kalt drau\u00dfen.\nB: Trink Tee und ruh dich aus.",exampleSrc:"A: I caught a cold.\nB: Again? Dress more warmly.\nA: Yes, it was too cold outside.\nB: Drink tea and rest.",funFact:"The verb form of Erk\u00e4ltung. Reflexive: 'sich erk\u00e4lten.' The Perfekt uses haben because it is reflexive. 'Ich habe mich erk\u00e4ltet' (I caught a cold)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sich erholen",src:"to recover, to recuperate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Reflexive. Er- + holen (to fetch).\nYou fetch yourself back from illness.",example:"A: Hast du dich von der Grippe erholt?\nB: Ja, ich habe mich gut erholt.\nA: Wie lange hat die Erholung gedauert?\nB: Etwa eine Woche.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you recovered from the flu?\nB: Yes, I have recovered well.\nA: How long did the recovery take?\nB: About a week.",funFact:"Beautiful metaphor: recovery is self-retrieval. You fetch yourself back from illness. 'Sich von einer Operation erholen' (to recover from an operation)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erholung",src:"the recovery, the recreation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From erholen + -ung.\n'Erholungsurlaub' = recovery vacation. Kur may be prescribed.",example:"A: Du brauchst Erholung.\nB: Ja, ich bin ersch\u00f6pft.\nA: Nimm dir ein paar Tage Erholung.\nB: Der Arzt hat mir eine Kur verschrieben.",exampleSrc:"A: You need rest.\nB: Yes, I am exhausted.\nA: Take a few days of rest.\nB: The doctor prescribed me a health retreat.",funFact:"In Germany, your doctor can prescribe a Kur (health retreat) for Erholung. The Krankenkasse may pay. Recovery is a medical right, not a luxury."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sch\u00e4tzen",src:"to estimate, to value, to appreciate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Three meanings in one verb.\n'Gesch\u00e4tzt' = approximately.",example:"A: Ich sch\u00e4tze die Kosten auf 500 Euro.\nB: Das ist eine grobe Sch\u00e4tzung.\nA: Ja, aber ich sch\u00e4tze, es wird nicht mehr.\nB: Ich sch\u00e4tze deine Ehrlichkeit.",exampleSrc:"A: I estimate the costs at 500 euros.\nB: That is a rough estimate.\nA: Yes, but I estimate it will not be more.\nB: I appreciate your honesty.",funFact:"Three meanings in one verb. 'Die Kosten sch\u00e4tzen' (to estimate costs). 'Ich sch\u00e4tze deine Hilfe' (I appreciate your help). A word of judgment and gratitude."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verteilen",src:"to distribute",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ver- + teilen (to share/divide). Inseparable.\n'Die Kosten werden verteilt.'",example:"A: Wer verteilt die Medikamente?\nB: Die Pflegerin verteilt sie.\nA: Wie werden die Kosten verteilt?\nB: Auf alle Versicherten gleichm\u00e4\u00dfig.",exampleSrc:"A: Who distributes the medicine?\nB: The caregiver distributes them.\nA: How are the costs distributed?\nB: Equally among all insured persons.",funFact:"The system distributes everything. 'Medikamente verteilen' (to distribute medicine). 'Die Kosten werden verteilt' (The costs are distributed). Inseparable prefix ver-."},
{type:"teach",trg:"behindern",src:"to hinder, to obstruct",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + hindern (to prevent).\n'Menschen mit Behinderung' = people with disabilities.",example:"A: Der Unfall behindert den Verkehr.\nB: Wie lange noch?\nA: Etwa eine Stunde.\nB: Dann nehme ich einen anderen Weg.",exampleSrc:"A: The accident is obstructing traffic.\nB: For how much longer?\nA: About an hour.\nB: Then I will take another route.",funFact:"'Behindert' as an adjective means 'disabled.' 'Menschen mit Behinderung' (people with disabilities) is the preferred modern phrase."},
{type:"teach",trg:"st\u00fcrzen",src:"to fall, to crash",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"'Er ist gest\u00fcrzt' = he fell.\nAlso: 'die Regierung st\u00fcrzen' = to topple the government.",example:"A: Was ist passiert?\nB: Er ist von der Leiter gest\u00fcrzt.\nA: Ist er verletzt?\nB: Ja, er hat sich den Arm gebrochen.",exampleSrc:"A: What happened?\nB: He fell from the ladder.\nA: Is he injured?\nB: Yes, he broke his arm.",funFact:"Falls in medicine, revolutions in politics. Same verb. 'Vom Fahrrad st\u00fcrzen' (to fall off the bicycle). 'Die Regierung st\u00fcrzen' (to topple the government)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ordination",src:"the doctor's office (Austrian)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Austrian German. In Germany: 'Arztpraxis.'\nKnowing both words helps across German-speaking countries.",example:"A: Wo ist die Ordination?\nB: In Wien sagt man Ordination.\nA: In Deutschland sagt man Arztpraxis.\nB: Ja, gleiche Sache, anderes Wort.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the doctor's office?\nB: In Vienna they say Ordination.\nA: In Germany they say Arztpraxis.\nB: Yes, same thing, different word.",funFact:"Austrian German. In Germany: 'Arztpraxis.' Regional vocabulary: knowing both words helps across German-speaking countries. Austria, Germany, and Switzerland all speak differently."},
{type:"teach",trg:"befreit",src:"exempt, freed",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'befreien' (to free).\n'Von der Zuzahlung befreit' = exempt from co-payment.",example:"A: Sind Sie von der Zuzahlung befreit?\nB: Ja, ich bin befreit.\nA: Dann m\u00fcssen Sie nichts extra zahlen.\nB: Gut, ich habe den Befreiungsausweis dabei.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you exempt from the co-payment?\nB: Yes, I am exempt.\nA: Then you do not have to pay anything extra.\nB: Good, I have the exemption card with me.",funFact:"In the insurance context: certain groups are befreit from paying extra. Low-income patients, children, and chronically ill people may be befreit von der Zuzahlung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"befriedigend",src:"satisfactory",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'befriedigen' (to satisfy).\nAlso a school grade: 3 = befriedigend.",example:"A: Wie war die Behandlung?\nB: Befriedigend. Nicht schlecht, nicht gro\u00dfartig.\nA: Also Note drei?\nB: Ja, genau. Befriedigend.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the treatment?\nB: Satisfactory. Not bad, not great.\nA: So grade three?\nB: Yes, exactly. Satisfactory.",funFact:"Also a school grade in Germany (3 = befriedigend). Not great, not terrible. The German grade of adequacy. 'Eine befriedigende L\u00f6sung' (a satisfactory solution)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kr\u00e4ftig",src:"strong, powerful, hearty",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Kraft' (strength/force).\n'Kr\u00e4ftig essen' = to eat heartily.",example:"A: Du siehst kr\u00e4ftig aus!\nB: Danke, ich trainiere viel.\nA: Und isst du kr\u00e4ftig?\nB: Ja, eine kr\u00e4ftige Suppe zum Mittag.",exampleSrc:"A: You look strong!\nB: Thanks, I train a lot.\nA: And do you eat heartily?\nB: Yes, a hearty soup for lunch.",funFact:"Conveys robust, physical strength. 'Eine kr\u00e4ftige Suppe' (a hearty soup). German comfort food is kr\u00e4ftig. From 'Kraft' (strength/force)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"parallel",src:"parallel",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Same in most European languages.\n'Die gesetzliche und private Versicherung laufen parallel.'",example:"A: Die beiden Systeme laufen parallel.\nB: Das gesetzliche und das private?\nA: Ja, parallel nebeneinander.\nB: Und welches ist besser?",exampleSrc:"A: The two systems run in parallel.\nB: The public and the private one?\nA: Yes, parallel to each other.\nB: And which one is better?",funFact:"In insurance: 'Die gesetzliche und private Versicherung laufen parallel' (public and private insurance run in parallel). Germany's dual healthcare system."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Mangel",src:"the lack, the deficiency",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"'Fachkr\u00e4ftemangel' = shortage of skilled workers.\n'Mangelware' = scarce commodity.",example:"A: Es gibt einen Mangel an Pflegern.\nB: Ja, der Pflegermangel ist ein gro\u00dfes Problem.\nA: Was kann man dagegen tun?\nB: Bessere Bezahlung und mehr Ausbildungspl\u00e4tze.",exampleSrc:"A: There is a shortage of caregivers.\nB: Yes, the caregiver shortage is a big problem.\nA: What can be done about it?\nB: Better pay and more training positions.",funFact:"Germany's healthcare system suffers from Pflegermangel (caregiver shortage). 'Fachkr\u00e4ftemangel' (shortage of skilled workers) is a national concern across many sectors."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Badewanne",src:"the bathtub",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Bade (bathing) + Wanne (tub).\nHaving a Badewanne instead of just a Dusche is a luxury.",example:"A: Hat die Wohnung eine Badewanne?\nB: Ja, eine gro\u00dfe Badewanne.\nA: Toll! Ich liebe es, in der Badewanne zu liegen.\nB: Die Badewanne ist fast neu.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the apartment have a bathtub?\nB: Yes, a large bathtub.\nA: Great! I love lying in the bathtub.\nB: The bathtub is almost new.",funFact:"In German apartments, having a Badewanne instead of just a Dusche is a luxury. Insurance covers bath aids for elderly patients. Bathing is healthcare in Germany."},
{type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-hildi-kitchen",trg:"Verumius nickt langsam. Das System, in das er eingezahlt hat, sch\u00fctzt ihn jetzt. Trotzdem versteht er die Formulare immer noch nicht. Also zeichnet Hildi ein neues Diagramm.",src:"Verumius nods slowly. The system he has paid into now protects him. Nevertheless, he still does not understand the forms. So Hildi draws a new diagram."},
{type:"story",speaker:"hildi",mood:"patient",art:"de-ber-hildi-napkin",trg:"Hildi nimmt eine Serviette und zeichnet zwei Kreise. 'Links: gesetzlich. Rechts: privat. Du bist hier.' Sie tippt auf den linken Kreis. Verumius f\u00fchlt sich zum ersten Mal orientiert.",src:"Hildi takes a napkin and draws two circles. 'Left: public. Right: private. You are here.' She taps the left circle. Verumius feels oriented for the first time."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"dawning-understanding",art:"de-ber-hildi-napkin",trg:"Also zahle ich jeden Monat, und daf\u00fcr bezahlt die Kasse den Arzt? Hildi nickt. 'Deshalb hei\u00dft es Solidarsystem. Alle zahlen, alle sind gesch\u00fctzt.' Das ergibt Sinn. Endlich.",src:"So I pay every month, and in return the fund pays the doctor? Hildi nods. 'That is why it is called a solidarity system. Everyone pays, everyone is protected.' That makes sense. Finally."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"satisfied",art:"de-ber-hildi-kitchen",trg:"Die Serviette ist voll mit Pfeilen, Kreisen und Ausrufezeichen. Es sieht aus wie ein Kunstwerk. Aber Verumius versteht jetzt mehr \u00fcber das deutsche Gesundheitssystem als die meisten Touristen nach zehn Jahren.",src:"The napkin is covered in arrows, circles, and exclamation marks. It looks like a work of art. But Verumius now understands more about the German healthcare system than most tourists after ten years."},
{type:"mc",q:"Hildi sagt: 'Die Krankenkasse, _____ du jeden Monat zahlst, hilft dir im Notfall.' Was passt?",opts:["an der","an den","an dem","an die"],ans:"an die",hint:"zahlen an + accusative. Krankenkasse is feminine. What is the feminine accusative?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Das Altenheim, in {1} meine Oma wohnt, ist sehr gut. {2} besuche ich sie oft.",blanks:{"1":"dem","2":"Deshalb"},pool:["dem","der","das","Deshalb","Trotzdem","Sonst"],hint:"First blank: in + dative, neuter Altenheim. Second blank: consequence conjunction.",sSrc:"The nursing home my grandma lives in is very good. Therefore I visit her often."}
]}

]};

export default UNIT_20;
